1489\u20131490\n|\n|-\n| [[Shamsuddin Muzaffar Shah]]\n| 1490\u20131494\n|\n|}\n\n;Hussain Shahi dynasty (1494-1538)\n{{Main|Hussain Shahi dynasty}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:180px;\"| Name\n! style=\"width:80px;\"| Reign\n! style=\"width:400px;\"| Notes\n|-\n| [[Alauddin Hussain Shah]]\n| 1494\u20131518\n|\n|-\n| [[Nasiruddin Nasrat Shah]]\n| 1518\u20131533\n|\n|-\n| [[Alauddin Firuz Shah II]]\n| 1533\n|\n|-\n| [[Ghiyasuddin Mahmud Shah]]\n| 1533\u20131538\n|\n|}\n\n;Governors under Suri rule (1539-1554)\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:180px;\"| Name\n! style=\"width:80px;\"| Reign\n! style=\"width:400px;\"| Notes\n|-\n| [[Khidr Khan(Bengal)|Khidr Khan]]\n| 1539\u20131541\n|Declared independence in 1541 and was replaced\n|-\n | [[Qazi Fazilat]]\n| 1541\u20131545\n|\n|-\n| [[Muhammad Khan Sur]]\n| 1545\u20131554\n|Declared independence upon the death of [[Islam Shah Suri]]\n|}\n\n;Muhammad Shah dynasty (1554-1564)\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:180px;\"| Name\n! style=\"width:80px;\"| Reign\n! style=\"width:400px;\"| Notes\n|-\n| [[Muhammad Khan Sur]]\n| 1554\u20131555\n| Declared independence and styled himself as ''Shamsuddin Muhammad Shah''\n|-\n| Ghiyasuddin Bahadur Shah I\n| 1555\u20131561\n|\n|-\n| [[Ghiyasuddin Jalal Shah]]\n| 1561\u20131563\n|\n|-\n| [[Ghiyasuddin Bahadur Shah II]]\n| 1563-1564\n|\n|}\n\n;Karrani dynasty (1564-1576)\n{{Main|Karrani dynasty}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:180px;\"| Name\n! style=\"width:80px;\"| Reign\n! style=\"width:400px;\"| Notes\n|-\n| [[Taj Khan Karrani]]\n| 1564\u20131566\n|\n|-\n| [[Sulaiman Khan Karrani]]\n| 1566\u20131572\n|\n|-\n| [[Bayazid Khan Karrani]]\n| 1572\n|\n|-\n| [[Daud Khan Karrani]]\n| 1572\u20131576\n|\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bengal Subah]]\n* [[List of rulers of Bengal]]\n* [[List of medieval great powers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commons category|Sultanate of Bengal}}\n* {{cite book |last=Yegar |first=Moshe |year=2002 |title=Between Integration and Secession: The Muslim Communities of the Southern Philippines, Southern Thailand, and Western Burma/Myanmar |location=Lanham, MD |publisher=Lexington Books |pages=23\u201324 |isbn=978-0-7391-0356-2}}\n* Hussain, Syed Ejaz (2003). The Bengal Sultanate: Politics, Economy and Coins, A.D. 1205\u20131576. Manohar. {{ISBN|978-81-7304-482-3}}.\n* ''The Grammar of Sultanate Mosque in Bengal Architecture'', Nujaba Binte Kabir (2012)\n\n{{coord|24|52|0|N|88|8|0|E|region:IN_type:country|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Bengal Sultanate|01]]\n[[Category:History of Bengal]]\n[[Category:Former sultanates]]\n[[Category:History of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:History of India]]\n[[Category:History of West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Bay of Bengal]]\n", "name_user": "UserNumber", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eForeign relations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bengal_Sultanate"}
{"title_page": "Tory Lanez", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian rapper and singer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{distinguish|gay boy spout}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Tory Lanez\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Tory Lanez 2500x1669.jpg\n| caption          = Peterson in 2016\n| alias            = Argentina Fargo<ref>[https://www.timeout.com/newyork/music/tory-lanez-interview-its-not-about-being-in-one-lane] {{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_name       = Daystar Peterson\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1992|7|27}}\n| birth_place      = [[Brampton]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[alternative R&B]]\n* [[Electronic music|electronic]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[dancehall]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Rapper\n* singer\n* composer\n* record producer\n}}\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| years_active     = 2009\u2013present\n| label           = {{flatlist|\n* [[Interscope Records|Interscope]] ( formerly)\n* Time is Money\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist| \n* [[6ix9ine]]\n* [[A Boogie wit da Hoodie]]\n* [[ASAP Ferg]]\n* [[Benny Blanco]]\n* [[G-Eazy]]\n* [[Mark Battles]]\n* [[Meek Mill]]\n* Play Picasso\n* [[Sean Kingston]]\n}}\n| website          = {{URL|https://swavenation.com/}}\n}}\n'''Daystar Peterson''' (born July 27, 1992), better known by his stage name '''Tory Lanez''', is a Canadian rapper, singer, composer, and record producer. He received initial recognition from the mixtape, ''Conflicts of My Soul: The 416 Story'' released in August 2013. In 2015, Tory Lanez signed to [[Benny Blanco]]'s [[Benny Blanco#Record Labels|Mad Love Records]] through [[Interscope Records]]. Lanez released his debut studio album, ''[[I Told You]]'', on August 19, 2016, which included the singles, \"[[Say It (Tory Lanez song)|Say It]]\" and \"[[Luv (Tory Lanez song)|Luv]]\", which peaked at number 23, and 19 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] respectively. His second album, ''[[Memories Don't Die]]'' was released on March 2, 2018. On October 26, 2018, Lanez released his third studio album, ''[[Love Me Now?]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nDaystar Peterson was born on July 27, 1992 in Canada to a [[Barbadians|Bajan]] father, Sonstar,<ref name=\"Bajan\">{{cite web|url=https://tufwalkingbillboard.wordpress.com/2011/07/19/tory-lanez-interview-whatsthaword-com/|title=Tory Lanez Interview \u2013 WhatsThaWorld.com &#124; The Ultimte Fly|date=July 19, 2011|accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> and [[Cura\u00e7ao]] and [[Guyanese people|Guyanese]] mother, Luella.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://saintheron.com/featured/get-tory-lanez/ |title=Get into It: Tory Lanez \u2013 Saint Heron |publisher=Saintheron.com |date=February 23, 2017 |accessdate=February 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kameir |first=Rawiya |url=http://www.thefader.com/2015/11/16/tory-lanez-gen-f-interview |title=Tory Lanez Isn't An Underdog Anymore |publisher=The Fader |date=November 16, 2015 |accessdate=February 28, 2017}}</ref> The family was based in [[Montreal]], before moving to [[Miami|Miami, Florida]].<ref name=\"time\">{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/newyork/music/tory-lanez-interview-its-not-about-being-in-one-lane|last=Vliet|first=Vivienne Van|date=October 14, 2014|title=Tory Lanez interview: 'It\u2019s not about being in one lane'}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/interviews/id.2395/title.tory-lanez-chronicles-his-journey-from-homelessness-to-a-list-collaborations|author=BRANDONE|date=May 13, 2014|title=Tory Lanez Chronicles His Journey From Homelessness To A-List Collaborations|accessdate=December 3, 2014}}</ref> Daystar was known to practice and refine his rapping skills throughout his childhood, before tragically finding out that his mother had died due to a rare disease. Following his mother's death, his father began working as an ordained [[Minister (Christianity)|minister]] and [[missionary]], causing them both to move frequently throughout the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtvhive.com/2013/05/31/tory-lanez-14-and-40s/|author=StacksBreadup|date=March 3, 2014|title=Tory Lanez's Biography}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtvhive.com/2013/05/31/tory-lanez-14-and-40s/|title=The Hard-Life Lows of Tory Lanez|last=Serrano|first=Shea|date=May 31, 2013}}</ref> Daystar's father later remarried and the family moved to [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]], where Daystar met his friend Hakeem, who at the time was a janitor. Daystar's nickname \"Lanez\" was given to him by Hakeem, as a comment on Daystar's thrill seeking tendencies, that sometimes saw him mucking around in the street, not looking for traffic and playing in the lanes.<ref name=\"neil\">{{cite web|url=http://stanfordartsreview.com/something-in-the-water-b-an-interview-with-tory-lanez/|title=Something in the Water, B: An Interview with Tory Lanez &#124; Stanford Arts Review|date=October 18, 2013|accessdate=July 10, 2015|author=Neil, Lawrence}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he was sent to live with his cousin Dahir Abib, Orane Forrest, in Jamaica, Queens, New York, because of his behavior issues. Daystar then was forced to return to Toronto with his grandmother. Since she refused to take care of him, he was on his own at the age of 15. \"I ended up moving downtown with these three dudes that I didn't really know. I came into the house and I didn't realize how things worked. From like fifteen to eighteen, I was just fighting them. It was every man for himself. That's what made me a man, having to fend for myself and being in a situation where there is no dad, no grandma and no mom to help you. It changed the person that I am today\", he says.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/01/tory-lanez-show-and-prove-xxl-magazine-winter-2015-issue/|title=Tory Lanez Can't Be Stopped in 2016|last=Johnson|first=Miranda|date=January 11, 2016|website=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|access-date=April 10, 2016}}</ref> He then once again started rapping, before giving himself a nickname, Notorious (which is a reference to the late rapper [[Notorious B.I.G.]], whom he idolized), and adopted into his new moniker \"Tory Lanez\". At the age of 16, Daystar dropped out of the tenth grade, and he would begin performing songs at the outdoor concerts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://greenmountainhiphop.com/tag/sean-kingston/|title=Sean Kingston &#124; Green Mountain Hip-Hop|date=March 20, 2012|accessdate=July 14, 2015|author=Stevie Beats}}</ref> At the age of 17, Daystar began singing, which he found an interest in. However, he had never received any vocal training.<ref name=\"neil\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiphopdx.com/interviews/id.2395/title.tory-lanez-chronicles-his-journey-from-homelessness-to-a-list-collaborations|title=Tory Lanez Chronicles His Journey From Homelessness To A-List Collaborations|date=May 14, 2014|accessdate=July 4, 2015|website=[[HipHopDX]]|author=Brandone}}</ref> Daystar also goes by the name Argentina Fargo. In an interview, he said \"When I put foreign and banking together, it's like foreign money. I\u2019m a Canadian dude, walking around America. When you look at me, it's like looking at foreign money. So I call myself Argentina Fargo\u2014like foreign money.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/music/tory-lanez-interview-its-not-about-being-in-one-lane|title=Tory Lanez interview: 'It\u2019s not about being in one lane'|newspaper=Time Out New York|access-date=January 28, 2017}}</ref> Among his musical inspirations growing up Lanez cites [[Brandy Norwood|Brandy]] and [[Ray J]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tsaay3lyA50|title=Tory Lanez Interview 2017 |date=January 28, 2017 |accessdate=January 28, 2017|website=MalcolmMusic}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2009\u201315: Career beginnings===\nIn 2009, Tory Lanez released his debut mixtape, ''T.L 2 T.O''.  While Lanez lived in [[South Florida]], he began directing some of his music videos, and posted them on his YouTube channel. [[Sean Kingston]] was interested in Lanez after seeing a video of him freestyling over [[Lloyd Banks]]' \"[[Beamer, Benz, or Bentley]]\".<ref name=\"Bajan\" /> In February 2010, Kingston contacted Lanez, telling him to meet up with him, during [[Justin Bieber]]'s tour and later got him to perform on there live.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=31c_LPqF1PI|date=January 24, 2011|title=History in the Making (Documentary) \u2013 Tory Lanez|accessdate=December 7, 2014}}</ref> In 2010, Lanez released the mixtapes, ''Just Landed, One Verse One Hearse, Playing for Keeps'' and ''Mr. 1 Verse Killah.'' In 2011, Lanez signed a record deal with Kingston's Time is Money Entertainment and released the mixtapes, ''Mr. Peterson, Chixtape,'' and ''Swavey''. He later left the label to be an independent artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/3295611-Tory-Lanez|title=Tory Lanez|publisher=discogs|access-date=May 25, 2016}}</ref> In 2012, Tory Lanez released the mixtape, ''Sincerely Tory, Conflicts of My Soul: The 416 Story'' in 2013, and ''Chixtape II'' in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.datpiff.com/Tory-Lanez-Sincerely-Tory-mixtape.351700.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Sincerely Tory|website=DatPiff|access-date=June 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/08/mixtape-premiere-tory-lanez-conflicts-of-my-soul-the-416-story|title=Mixtape Premiere: Tory Lanez \"Conflicts Of My Soul: The 416 Story\"|website=Complex|access-date=June 2, 2016}}</ref> In April 2014, Tory released two episodes of the \"Public Swave Announcement\", of behind the scenes of the \"These Things Happen Tour\" with [[G-Eazy]] and [[Rockie Fresh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-public-swave-announcement-episode-1-new-video.27593.html|title=Tory Lanez 'Public Swave Announcement' Episode 1 [New Video]|author=De Loen, Mike|date=April 16, 2014|accessdate=July 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-public-swave-announcement-episode-2-new-video.27733.html|title=Tory Lanez 'Public Swave Announcement' Episode 2 [New Video]|date=April 23, 2014|author=James, Nicolas|accessdate=July 7, 2015}}</ref> On June 2, 2014, Lanez released the song, \"Teyana\", as a tribute to singer [[Teyana Taylor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-teyana-new-song.1909077.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Teyana {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=June 2, 2016}}</ref> Taylor responded with the track, \"Dreams of Fuckin' an R&B Bitch\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://watchloud.com/teyana-taylor-responds-tory-lanez-track/|title=Teyana Taylor Responds To Tory Lanez With \u2018Dreams of F*ckin An R&B B*tch\u2019|author=Kymmi|date=September 26, 2014|accessdate=May 31, 2015|publisher=watchloud.com}}</ref> On June 6, 2014, Lanez released, \"The Godfather\", a song to announce that he was going to start a series called, ''Fargo Fridays'', only releasing songs, albums, or videos on Fridays on HotNewHipHop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-the-godfather-prod-by-playback-and-tory-lanez-new-song.1911343.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 The Godfather (Prod. By PlayBack & Tory Lanez) {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=June 2, 2016}}</ref> The songs, \"I'll Be There\", \"Talk On Road\", and \"Balenciagas\" were released later that month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-i-ll-be-there-feat-meek-mill-french-montana-new-song.1916311.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 I'll Be There Feat. Meek Mill & French Montana {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=June 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/torylanez/talk-on-road-prod-daniel-worthy-x-tory-lanez-x-the-mekanics|title=Talk On Road (Prod. The MeKanics x Daniel Worthy x Tory Lanez)|website=SoundCloud|access-date=June 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-balenciagas-prod-by-tory-lanez-and-play-picasso-new-song.1925308.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Balenciagas (Prod. By Tory Lanez & Play Picasso) {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=June 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter releasing a bunch of songs from the series, he released a song called, \"The Mission\" to celebrate his tour announcement on August 14, 2014. Lanez kicked off his first headlining tour, the \"Lost Cause Tour\", in conjunction with the mixtape, ''[[Lost Cause (Tory Lanez mixtape)|Lost Cause]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-the-mission-new-song.1956003.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 The Mission {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=June 2, 2016}}</ref> The mixtape was supposed to be released on September 29, 2014, but got pushed back to October 1. In an interview, Tory Lanez claimed he has ghost-written songs for artists such as [[Akon]] (\"[[Seen It All: The Autobiography|Been Gettin' Money]]\" with [[Jeezy]]), [[Casey Veggies]] (\"[[Live & Grow|Actin' Up]]\"), [[August Alsina]] (\"[[Dreams Worth More Than Money|My Niggas]]\" with Meek Mill), as well as [[T.I.]] and [[Travis Scott]].<ref>[http://genius.com/artists/tory-lanez] {{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-talks-teyana-taylor-lost-cause-and-toronto-s-music-scene-news.12565.html|title=Tory Lanez Talks Teyana Taylor, \"Lost Cause\", and Toronto Music Scene|date=October 22, 2014|author=Lyons, Patrick|accessdate=May 31, 2015}}</ref> On February 27, 2015, Tory Lanez revealed that he was going to release a collaboration EP with the WeDidIt Records producers on April 6.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2015/02/27/tory-lanez-henny-in-hand-1|title=Watch Tory Lanez' Video For \"Henny in Hand\"|date=February 27, 2015|website=[[The Fader]]|accessdate=May 31, 2015|author=Trammel, Matthew}}</ref> On April 3, 2015, Tory released the single titled \"In For It\" for his upcoming EP.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-in-for-it-prod-by-rl-grime-new-song.1963835.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 In For It (Prod. By RL Grime)|date=April 3, 2015|accessdate=May 10, 2015|author=Lyons, Patrick}}</ref> On May 8, 2015, Lanez released another song, titled \"Ric Flair\" featuring Rory Trustory. On May 22, 2015, he released the second single for the EP, titled \"Acting Like\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-acting-like-prod-by-shlohmo-new-song.1964595.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Acting Like (Prod. By Shlohmo) &#124; Stream & Listen [New Song]|date=May 22, 2015|accessdate=May 31, 2015|author=Lilah, Rose}}</ref> On June 19, 2015, Tory announced that the EP would be called, ''[[Cruel Intentions (album)|Cruel Intentions]]'' and released on June 26, 2015. That same day the single, \"[[Karrueche Tran|Karrueche]]\" was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-karrueche-prod-by-noah-breakfast-new-song.1965033.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Karrueche (Prod. By Noah Breakfast) &#124; Stream & Listen [New Song]|date=June 19, 2015|website=hotnewhiphop.com|accessdate=June 20, 2015|author=Lilah, Rose}}</ref>\n\n=== 2015\u2013present: ''I Told You'', ''Memories Don't Die'', ''Love Me Now'', ''Chixtape 5'' and ''The New Toronto 3'' ===\nOn July 15, 2015, Tory Lanez released the first single off his debut album, titled \"[[Say It (Tory Lanez song)|Say It]]\". It was also revealed that he signed to [[Benny Blanco]]'s [[Benny Blanco#Record Labels|Mad Love Records]] and [[Interscope Records]]. On September 18, 2015, Lanez released the single, \"[[B.L.O.W. (song)|BLOW]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-blow-new-song.1966344.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 B.L.O.W. (Prod. By Play Picasso & Sergio R) {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=March 11, 2016}}</ref> December 25, 2015, Lanez released the two mixtapes, ''[[Chixtape III]]'' and ''[[The New Toronto]]''. On January 18, 2016, \"[[LA Confidential (song)|LA Confidential]]\" was released as the second single for the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-la-confidential-new-song.1968319.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 LA Confidential {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=March 12, 2016}}</ref> On January 28, 2016, Tory Lanez made a guest appearance on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' By performing \"Say It\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-performs-say-it-with-brownstone-on-jimmy-kimmel-live-new-video.36649.html|title=Tory Lanez Performs 'Say It' With Brownstone On Jimmy Kimmel Live!|date=January 28, 2016|accessdate=March 14, 2016|website=HotNewHipHop|author=Walker, Angus}}</ref> A month later, Lanez released a remix of [[MadeinTYO]]'s \"[[Uber Everywhere]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-uber-everywhere-new-song.1968717.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Uber Everywhere  {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=March 12, 2016}}</ref> On March 4, 2016, Lanez released the song, \"Tim Duncan\" as a part of his ''Fargo Fridays'' series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-tim-duncan-prod-by-c-sick-new-song.1968824.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Tim Duncan (Prod. By C-Sick) {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=March 12, 2016}}</ref> He released the song, \"Real Addresses\" the next week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-real-addresses-new-song.1968916.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Real Addresses {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=March 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, 2016, [[ASAP Ferg]] and Tory Lanez announced \"The Level Up Tour\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/asap-ferg-and-tory-lanez-announce-the-level-up-tour-news.20883.html|title=ASAP Ferg & Tory Lanez Announce \"The Level Up Tour\"|last=Schwartz|first=Danny|date=April 1, 2016|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=April 9, 2016}}</ref> On April 5, 2016, it was revealed that Tory Lanez would perform at [[Summer Jam]] and [[Pemberton Music Festival]] in the summer of 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/summer-jam-festival-stage-line-up-includes-chance-the-rapper-tory-lanez-and-desiigner-news.20935.html|title=Summer Jam Festival Stage Line-Up Includes Chance The Rapper, Tory Lanez & Desiigner|last=Lilah|first=Rose|date=April 5, 2016|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=April 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/j-cole-snoop-dogg-wiz-khalifa-and-ice-cube-to-headline-pemberton-2016-news.20945.html|title=J. Cole, Snoop Dogg, Wiz Khalifa, & Ice Cube To Headline Pemberton 2016|last=Schwartz|first=Danny|date=April 5, 2016|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=April 9, 2016}}</ref> On April 8, 2016, Tory Lanez and ASAP Ferg collaborated on the song, \"Line Up the Flex\" to promote their \"Level Up\" tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-and-asap-ferg-line-up-the-flex-prod-by-play-picasso-new-song.1969314.html|title=Tory Lanez & A$AP Ferg \u2013 Line Up The Flex (Prod. By Play Picasso) &#124; Stream [New Song]|last=Lilah|first=Rose|date=April 8, 2016|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=April 9, 2016}}</ref> On April 18, Tory Lanez refused to be on the 2016 XXL Freshmen cover because he felt he was in a higher league musically than the other artists being considered.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.designntrend.com/articles/74225/20160418/tory-lanez-refuses-2016-xxl-freshman-cover-pulls-himself-out.htm|title=Tory Lanez Refuses To Be On 2016 XXL Freshman Cover, Pulls Himself Out: 'Don't Be Confused'|date=April 18, 2016|website=Design & Trend|access-date=May 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/04/tory-lanez-shots-at-drake/|title=Five Times Tory Lanez Took Shots at Drake|last=Weinstein|first=Max|date=April 18, 2016|website=XXL|access-date=May 16, 2016}}</ref> On May 6, 2016, Lanez released two songs, \"For Real\" and \"Unforgetful\" as a part of the ''Fargo Friday'' series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-for-real-new-song.1969672.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 For Real {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=May 9, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-unforgetful-prod-by-london-on-da-track-new-song.1969674.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Unforgetful (Prod. By London On Da Track) {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=May 9, 2016}}</ref> On July 29, 2016, Lanez released the official second single \"[[Luv (Tory Lanez song)|Luv]]\" on [[iTunes]]. He also revealed that his album title would be ''[[I Told You]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-luv-prod-by-benny-blanco-and-cashmere-cat-new-song.1970139.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Luv (Prod. By Benny Blanco & Cashmere Cat) &#124; Stream [New Song]|last=Lilah|first=Rose|date=June 10, 2016|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=June 10, 2016}}</ref> ''I Told You'' was released on August 19, 2016. On July 5, Lanez released two remixes for [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]'s \"[[Controlla]]\" and [[DJ Khaled]]'s \"[[I Got the Keys]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/66703-tory-lanez-remixes-drakes-controlla-listen/|title=Tory Lanez Remixes Drake's \"Controlla\": Listen|last=Lozano|first=Kevin|date=July 10, 2016|website=[[Pitchfork Media]]|access-date=July 23, 2016}}</ref> On July 20, Lanez announced the I Told You tour to promote the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.39692/title.tory-lanez-announces-album-release-date-tour|title=Tory Lanez Announces Album Release Date & Tour|last=Mitchell|first=Chris|date=July 20, 2016|website=HipHopDX|access-date=July 23, 2016}}</ref>\nOn March 2, 2018, Lanez released his second studio album, ''[[Memories Don't Die]]''. Within the same year, he has also released an album titled ''[[Love Me Now? (album)|Love Me Now?]]'' on October 26, 2018,<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-shares-love-me-now-release-date-and-cover-art-news.62067.html |title=Tory Lanez Shares \"Love Me Now\" Release Date & Cover Art |website=Hotnewhiphop.com |date=2018-10-12 |accessdate=2020-04-16}}</ref> He also released an album titled ''[[Chixtape 5]]'' on November 15, 2019, and another album titled ''[[The New Toronto 3]]'' on April 10, 2020.<ref>{{cite|url=https://www.nme.com/big-reads/tory-lanez-cover-interview-2020-words-are-so-powerful-death-and-life-is-in-the-power-of-your-tongue-2624318|title=Tory Lanez: \u201cWords are so powerful. Death and life is in the power of your tongue\u201d|website=NME|last=Perry|first=Kevin EG|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, 2020, Lanez teamed up with Jamaican [[reggae]] singer [[Buju Banton]] for a remix of \"Trust\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dancehallmag.com/2020/03/20/music/epic-fail-for-buju-bantons-trust-remix-with-tory-lanez.html|title=Epic Fail For Buju Banton's \u2018Trust\u2019 Remix With Tory Lanez|date=March 20, 2020|website=dancehallmag.com|accessdate=March 21, 2020|author=Baugh, Claudine}}</ref>\n\n== Musical style ==\nIn an interview on Nice Kicks with Ian Stonebook, Lanez described his own personal style he calls, Swavey: \"Swavey is a two-adjective word. A lot of people use it as an attribute, but the real definition of swavey is a genre of music. The genre of music is the genre of fusing more than one together. I know it sounds strange, but if you ask an artist what they do they're going to say that they rap, they sing, they do rock, a lot of people are multi-talented. They get looked at confused, but I don't think that they're confused. I feel that they're just talented, swavey artists. Labels want to put you in one lane, but I feel like there are so many people are more than that and they're swavey artists.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nicekicks.com/2012/10/14/tory-lanez-talks-air-jordans-music-industry-advice-staying-swavey/|title=Tory Lanez Talks Air Jordans, Music Industry Advice & Staying Swavey &#124; Nice Kicks|date=October 14, 2012|accessdate=July 7, 2015|author=Stonebook, Ian}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n\n===Drake===\nIn 2010, Lanez posted a video on YouTube, challenging fellow Canadian [[rapper]] [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]], to whom he was rumored to be related. The video features him denying these rumors and announcing the $10,000 challenge. While showing Drake respect, Lanez again challenged him, but only if Drake would listen to some of his tracks from his second mixtape ''Playing for Keeps''. Lanez also claimed that if Drake did not like it, he would personally give to him $10,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://torylanez.wordpress.com/about/|title=Biography The Official Tory Lanez Fansite|accessdate=December 3, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://drizzy.ning.com/m/discussion?id=3514281%3ATopic%3A110007|title=Tory Lanez $10,000 Challenge To Drake (Who Do Ya'll Think?)|date=March 27, 2010|author=Kevin G|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref> In August 2015, while appearing on the \"Sway in the Morning\" radio show on [[Shade 45]], Lanez had taken a shot at Drake, alluding to the infamous freestyle he had performed on [[Hot 97]] six years prior where he had read lyrics from his [[BlackBerry]]. In October 2015, Lanez created additional tension with the rapper when he expressed his dislike of the use of \"the 6\", a nickname for Toronto, and one that had, of course, been popularized by Drake.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rapdose.com/2015/10/12/tory-lanez-disses-drake-says-its-not-cool-to-call-toronto-the-6/|title=Tory Lanez Disses Drake, Says It's Not Cool To Call Toronto \"The 6\"|website=Rapdose.com|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the lyrics of his 2016 single \"[[Summer Sixteen]]\", Drake appears to make a subliminal diss at Lanez, rapping: \"All you boys in the new Toronto want to be me a little.\" Many took this, and the ensuing lines, to be something off a shot taken towards Tory Lanez. Drake also took aim at [[Meek Mill]] who, in the midst of their ongoing feud, called out Drake for dissing Lanez on the song, \"[[War Pain]]\": \"Tory from the 6, you hatin\u2019 on him, Lord knows!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/drake-goes-after-meek-mill-barack-obama-and-tory-lanez-on-summer-sixteen-news.19888.html|title=Drake Goes After Meek Mill, Barack Obama & Tory Lanez On \"Summer Sixteen\"|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=March 12, 2016}}</ref> In an interview with [[Revolt (TV network)|Revolt]], Tory was asked about the perceived shot. He was skeptical about whether it was aimed at him at all, he assured the press that he wouldn't be responding even if it was. \"Drake could diss me 20,000 times, and I\u2019d never diss him. I\u2019m a fan... I have no negativity on my side. All blessings to that man.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-on-drake-id-never-diss-him-im-a-fan-news.20159.html|title=Tory Lanez On Drake: \"I'd Never Diss Him \u2013 I'm A Fan\"|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=March 12, 2016}}</ref> When Tory released his version of, \"Uber Everywhere\", he raps, \"Pussy boy, smack that smile clean off your face / You don't know no trap niggas, you don't be around this way / You some actor nigga boy, I used to see you on the screen\". Many people thought Tory was taking shots at Drake. Tory disses Drake again in the song, \"Line Up the Flex\" with ASAP Ferg. Lanez rapped \"I was never gang, gang, gang, gang/ I was One Umbrella Mob\", in a response to Drake's shot at him on \"Summer Sixteen\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDrake fired back in the song, \"Still Here\" on the album, [[Views (album)|''Views'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/04/drake-views-from-the-6-album-subliminal-shots/|title=10 Subliminal Shots on Drake's 'Views' Album \u2013 XXL|website=XXL Mag|access-date=May 17, 2016}}</ref> In an interview with [[Zane Lowe]] on [[Beats 1]], Drake spoke on Tory: \"I encourage anybody to go out there and do the most damage that you possibly can. Do you things. Get all the fruits. Get everything. Become the biggest artist you can possibly be. Just don't get up there finally and start talking down on me, especially when we have no interaction.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.designntrend.com/articles/75288/20160502/drake-talks-torey-lanez-beef-blasts-young-rappper-trying-diss.htm|title=Drake Talks Torey Lanez Beef, Blasts Young Rapper For Trying To Diss Him|last=Nelson|first=Daryl|date=May 2, 2016|website=Design & Trend|access-date=May 16, 2016}}</ref> Tory took shots at Drake again in the song, \"For Real\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/new-music/2016/05/tory-lanez-drake-shots-for-real/|title=Tory Lanez Baits Drake Once More With Shots on 'For Real'|last=Ivey|first=Justin|date=May 6, 2016|website=XXL|access-date=May 16, 2016}}</ref> On June 27, 2016, Lanez talked to Ebro on the Ebro in the Morning show and he stated about [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]] and said \"Hip-hop is a contact sport, I'm here to compete, I'm here to be #1.\" He goes on to say, \"I was a fan of his music before, no one's ever took that from me. That doesn't mean I'm not here to take my crown.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-on-drake-we-cant-share-first-place-news.22509.html?|title=Ready to take crown|last=Lilah|first=Rose|date=June 27, 2016|website=Hotnewhiphop|access-date=June 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Jacquees===\nIn February 2016, [[Jacquees]] tweeted, \"[[Chris Brown|Chris [Brown]]] my idol/big bro he don't count never will but you other guys im at yo throat #FuckHowYouFeel\". The tweet meant that Jacquees is in a fierce competition with every [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] artist in the game, except for [[Chris Brown]], who he says is his idol. The tweet wasn't convincing to Lanez, who responded to Jacquees with two choice emojis. Jacquees took Lanez' emoji response as an assault, and he went on to call Lanez a \"peasant\" and \"watermelon head ass\". Jacquees did, however, take the time to compliment Lanez' penmanship, though he implied that Lanez' vocal talents are not up to par with his own. Lanez still hasn't responded to Jacquees, but tells his fans to \"advise that boy\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/jacquees-challenges-randb-competition-tory-lanez-responds-news.20366.html|title=Jacquees Challenges R&B Competition, Tory Lanez Responds|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=March 12, 2016}}</ref> The two later squashed their beef at [[South by Southwest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-and-jacquees-have-squashed-their-beef-news.20683.html|title=Tory Lanez & Jacquees Have Squashed Their Beef|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=March 20, 2016}}</ref> They later announced in August 2016 that they were going on tour together.\n\n=== Joyner Lucas ===\nIn November 2018, during an [[Instagram]] Live session, Lanez claimed that he's a better rapper than American rapper [[Joyner Lucas]].<ref name=\"Jahmal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-is-resurrecting-friendly-competition-in-hip-hop-news.70768.html|title=Tory Lanez Is Resurrecting Friendly Competition in Hip-Hop|last=Jahmal|first=Karlton|date=n.d.|website=HotNewHipHop|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 12, 2019}}</ref> In response, Lucas challenged Lanez to a [[Battle rap|rap battle]], which led to several diss records being released between the two, including the \"[[Lucky You (song)|Lucky You]] Freestyle\" and the \"[[Zeze (song)|Zeze]] Freestyle\".<ref name=\"Jahmal\"/> Although the beef was short lived, Lanez expressed distaste at those who sided with Lucas.<ref name=\"Jahmal\"/> The end of the beef was once more evident when the two released a remix of [[DaBaby]]'s song [[Suge (DaBaby song)|Suge]].\n\n=== Don Q ===\nShortly after his beef with Joyner Lucas ensued, New York rapper [[Don Q (rapper)|Don Q]] dropped a battle track titled \"I'm Not Joyner\", alleging that Lanez was stealing Q's lyrics.<ref name=\"Jahmal\"/> Lanez fired back with a track called \"Dom Queen\", before Q responded with another diss track.<ref name=\"Jahmal\"/> Another rapper, [[Dreamville Records|Dreamville]] artist [[JID]] was involved into the beef, seemingly displeased with previous statements Lanez made aimed at his mentor, [[J. Cole]].<ref name=\"Jahmal\"/> Lanez then challenged the entire Dreamville artist roster in response, with rappers including Dreamdoll responding with their own tracks aimed at Lanez.<ref name=\"Jahmal\"/>\n\n=== Response ===\nIn response to Tory Lanez's various rap beefs, Karlton Jahmal of Hip-hop publication ''HotNewHipHop'' said \"the art of the competitive, lyrical battle rap has been missing from the mainstream wave for years...\", until Lanez brought the culture exactly what it's been missing with his friendly yet competitive take. Jahmal concluded that Lanez was essentially \"engineering an overall shift back to the roots of hip-hop [...] more about proving lyrical talent than they are about utterly destroying an opponent\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-is-resurrecting-friendly-competition-in-hip-hop-news.70768.html|title=Tory Lanez Is Resurrecting Friendly Competition in Hip-Hop|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=July 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Legal issues==\nOn March 26, 2016, during a concert in [[Midland, Texas]], violent scuffles between security forces and concertgoers occurred. Lanez then proceeded to tell the crowd to \"fuck shit up,\" which incited a full-on riot and forced police to shut down the show. Multiple people were arrested. The venue and concert promoters are considering legal actions against Lanez.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.38087/title.tory-lanez-incites-riot-cops-shut-down-texas-concert|title=Tory Lanez Incites Riot & Cops Shut Down Texas Concert|last=Hernandez|first=Victoria|date=March 28, 2016|website=[[HipHopDX]]|access-date=April 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Tory Lanez discography}}\n* ''[[I Told You]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Memories Don't Die]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Love Me Now?]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Chixtape 5]]'' (2019) \n* ''[[The New Toronto 3]]'' (2020)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Awards\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n|2015\n|[[2015 Much Music Video Awards|Much Music Video Awards]]\n|[[MuchMusic Video Award for Best Rap Video|Best Hip Hop Video]]\n|\"Henny in Hand\"\n|rowspan=\"8\" {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|2016\n|[[BET Awards 2016|BET Awards]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.39389/title.the-full-list-of-bet-award-winners-2016 | title=The Full List Of BET Award Winners 2016 | work=[[HipHopDX]] | date=June 26, 2016 | accessdate=August 22, 2016}}</ref>\n|[[BET Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|Himself\n|-\n|[[2016 BET Hip Hop Awards|BET Hip Hop Awards]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.complex.com/music/2016/08/bet-hip-hop-awards-2016-nominees | title=Here Are the Nominees for BET's 2016 Hip-Hop Awards | work=Complex | date=August 18, 2016 | accessdate=August 22, 2016}}</ref>\n|Best New Hip Hop Artist\n|-\n| [[MOBO Awards]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.glasgowlive.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/mobo-awards-2016-nominations-announced-11916262 | title=MOBO Awards 2016 nominations announced: Find out who made the shortlist | work=Glasgow Live | date=September 21, 2016 | accessdate=September 21, 2016}}</ref>\n| Best International Act\n|-\n| [[2016 Soul Train Music Awards|Soul Train Music Awards]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rap-up.com/2016/10/12/drake-leads-soul-train-awards-2016-nominations/ | title=Drake Leads Soul Train Awards 2016 Nominations | work=Rap-Up | date=October 12, 2016 | accessdate=October 13, 2016}}</ref>\n| [[Soul Train Music Award for Best R&B/Soul or Rap New Artist|Best New Artist]]\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2017\n| [[59th Annual Grammy Awards|Grammy Awards]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7597556/grammys-nominees-complete-list-2017 | title=Here Is the Complete List of Nominees for the 2017 Grammys | work=Billboard | date=December 6, 2016 | accessdate=December 6, 2016}}</ref>\n| [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Song|Best R&B Song]]\n| \"[[Luv (Tory Lanez song)|Luv]]\"\n|-\n| rowspan=3|[[Juno Awards of 2017|Juno Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Juno Awards Nominees 2017: Here's the Full Nominations List|url=http://www.flare.com/celebrity/entertainment/juno-awards-nominees-2017/|website=Flare|accessdate=March 13, 2017|date=February 7, 2017}}</ref>\n| Fan Choice Award\n| rowspan=2|Himself\n|-\n| Breakthrough Artist of the Year\n|-\n| Rap Recording of the Year\n| \"Shooters\"\n|{{won}}<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/music/junos/news/junos-2018-the-complete-list-of-winners-1.4579405 \"Junos 2018: the complete list of winners\"]. CBC News,  \u00b7 March 25, 2018</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|2019\n|[[50th NAACP Image Awards|NAACP Image Awards]]\n|Best New Artist\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Himself\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3|[[Juno Awards of 2019|Juno Awards]]\n| Fan Choice Award\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{nom}}\n|-\n| Artist of the Year\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Juno Award for Rap Recording of the Year|Rap Recording]]\n|''Love Me Now?''\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|2019\n|[[2019 BET Hip Hop Awards|BET Hip Hop Awards]]\n|Best International Flow \n|rowspan=\"3\"|Himself\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3|[[Juno Awards of 2020|Juno Awards]]\n| Fan Choice Award\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{Pending}}\n|-\n| Artist of the Year\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{Pending}}\n|-\n| [[Juno Award for Rap Recording of the Year|Rap Recording]]\n|''Freaky''\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{Pending}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|2020\n|[[Juno Awards]]\n|[[Juno Award for R&B/Soul Recording of the Year]]\n|''Chixtape 5''\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{Pending}}\n|-\n|[[Juno Awards]]\n|[[Juno Award for R&B/Soul Recording of the Year]]\n|''Feel It Too''\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{Pending}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{SoundCloud}}\n*{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=mn0002775792}}\n\n{{Tory Lanez}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lanez, Tory}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Black Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Barbadian descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Cura\u00e7aoan descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian male rappers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian rappers]]\n[[Category:Interscope Records artists]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Rap Recording of the Year winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian rapper and singer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{distinguish|Yung Tory}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Tory Lanez\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Tory Lanez 2500x1669.jpg\n| caption          = Peterson in 2016\n| alias            = Argentina Fargo<ref>[https://www.timeout.com/newyork/music/tory-lanez-interview-its-not-about-being-in-one-lane] {{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_name       = Daystar Peterson\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1992|7|27}}\n| birth_place      = [[Brampton]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[alternative R&B]]\n* [[Electronic music|electronic]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[dancehall]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Rapper\n* singer\n* composer\n* record producer\n}}\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| years_active     = 2009\u2013present\n| label           = {{flatlist|\n* [[Interscope Records|Interscope]] ( formerly)\n* Time is Money\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist| \n* [[6ix9ine]]\n* [[A Boogie wit da Hoodie]]\n* [[ASAP Ferg]]\n* [[Benny Blanco]]\n* [[G-Eazy]]\n* [[Mark Battles]]\n* [[Meek Mill]]\n* Play Picasso\n* [[Sean Kingston]]\n}}\n| website          = {{URL|https://swavenation.com/}}\n}}\n'''Daystar Peterson''' (born July 27, 1992), better known by his stage name '''Tory Lanez''', is a Canadian rapper, singer, composer, and record producer. He received initial recognition from the mixtape, ''Conflicts of My Soul: The 416 Story'' released in August 2013. In 2015, Tory Lanez signed to [[Benny Blanco]]'s [[Benny Blanco#Record Labels|Mad Love Records]] through [[Interscope Records]]. Lanez released his debut studio album, ''[[I Told You]]'', on August 19, 2016, which included the singles, \"[[Say It (Tory Lanez song)|Say It]]\" and \"[[Luv (Tory Lanez song)|Luv]]\", which peaked at number 23, and 19 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] respectively. His second album, ''[[Memories Don't Die]]'' was released on March 2, 2018. On October 26, 2018, Lanez released his third studio album, ''[[Love Me Now?]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nDaystar Peterson was born on July 27, 1992 in Canada to a [[Barbadians|Bajan]] father, Sonstar,<ref name=\"Bajan\">{{cite web|url=https://tufwalkingbillboard.wordpress.com/2011/07/19/tory-lanez-interview-whatsthaword-com/|title=Tory Lanez Interview \u2013 WhatsThaWorld.com &#124; The Ultimte Fly|date=July 19, 2011|accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> and [[Cura\u00e7ao]] and [[Guyanese people|Guyanese]] mother, Luella.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://saintheron.com/featured/get-tory-lanez/ |title=Get into It: Tory Lanez \u2013 Saint Heron |publisher=Saintheron.com |date=February 23, 2017 |accessdate=February 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kameir |first=Rawiya |url=http://www.thefader.com/2015/11/16/tory-lanez-gen-f-interview |title=Tory Lanez Isn't An Underdog Anymore |publisher=The Fader |date=November 16, 2015 |accessdate=February 28, 2017}}</ref> The family was based in [[Montreal]], before moving to [[Miami|Miami, Florida]].<ref name=\"time\">{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/newyork/music/tory-lanez-interview-its-not-about-being-in-one-lane|last=Vliet|first=Vivienne Van|date=October 14, 2014|title=Tory Lanez interview: 'It\u2019s not about being in one lane'}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/interviews/id.2395/title.tory-lanez-chronicles-his-journey-from-homelessness-to-a-list-collaborations|author=BRANDONE|date=May 13, 2014|title=Tory Lanez Chronicles His Journey From Homelessness To A-List Collaborations|accessdate=December 3, 2014}}</ref> Daystar was known to practice and refine his rapping skills throughout his childhood, before tragically finding out that his mother had died due to a rare disease. Following his mother's death, his father began working as an ordained [[Minister (Christianity)|minister]] and [[missionary]], causing them both to move frequently throughout the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtvhive.com/2013/05/31/tory-lanez-14-and-40s/|author=StacksBreadup|date=March 3, 2014|title=Tory Lanez's Biography}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtvhive.com/2013/05/31/tory-lanez-14-and-40s/|title=The Hard-Life Lows of Tory Lanez|last=Serrano|first=Shea|date=May 31, 2013}}</ref> Daystar's father later remarried and the family moved to [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]], where Daystar met his friend Hakeem, who at the time was a janitor. Daystar's nickname \"Lanez\" was given to him by Hakeem, as a comment on Daystar's thrill seeking tendencies, that sometimes saw him mucking around in the street, not looking for traffic and playing in the lanes.<ref name=\"neil\">{{cite web|url=http://stanfordartsreview.com/something-in-the-water-b-an-interview-with-tory-lanez/|title=Something in the Water, B: An Interview with Tory Lanez &#124; Stanford Arts Review|date=October 18, 2013|accessdate=July 10, 2015|author=Neil, Lawrence}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he was sent to live with his cousin Dahir Abib, Orane Forrest, in Jamaica, Queens, New York, because of his behavior issues. Daystar then was forced to return to Toronto with his grandmother. Since she refused to take care of him, he was on his own at the age of 15. \"I ended up moving downtown with these three dudes that I didn't really know. I came into the house and I didn't realize how things worked. From like fifteen to eighteen, I was just fighting them. It was every man for himself. That's what made me a man, having to fend for myself and being in a situation where there is no dad, no grandma and no mom to help you. It changed the person that I am today\", he says.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/01/tory-lanez-show-and-prove-xxl-magazine-winter-2015-issue/|title=Tory Lanez Can't Be Stopped in 2016|last=Johnson|first=Miranda|date=January 11, 2016|website=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|access-date=April 10, 2016}}</ref> He then once again started rapping, before giving himself a nickname, Notorious (which is a reference to the late rapper [[Notorious B.I.G.]], whom he idolized), and adopted into his new moniker \"Tory Lanez\". At the age of 16, Daystar dropped out of the tenth grade, and he would begin performing songs at the outdoor concerts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://greenmountainhiphop.com/tag/sean-kingston/|title=Sean Kingston &#124; Green Mountain Hip-Hop|date=March 20, 2012|accessdate=July 14, 2015|author=Stevie Beats}}</ref> At the age of 17, Daystar began singing, which he found an interest in. However, he had never received any vocal training.<ref name=\"neil\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiphopdx.com/interviews/id.2395/title.tory-lanez-chronicles-his-journey-from-homelessness-to-a-list-collaborations|title=Tory Lanez Chronicles His Journey From Homelessness To A-List Collaborations|date=May 14, 2014|accessdate=July 4, 2015|website=[[HipHopDX]]|author=Brandone}}</ref> Daystar also goes by the name Argentina Fargo. In an interview, he said \"When I put foreign and banking together, it's like foreign money. I\u2019m a Canadian dude, walking around America. When you look at me, it's like looking at foreign money. So I call myself Argentina Fargo\u2014like foreign money.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/music/tory-lanez-interview-its-not-about-being-in-one-lane|title=Tory Lanez interview: 'It\u2019s not about being in one lane'|newspaper=Time Out New York|access-date=January 28, 2017}}</ref> Among his musical inspirations growing up Lanez cites [[Brandy Norwood|Brandy]] and [[Ray J]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tsaay3lyA50|title=Tory Lanez Interview 2017 |date=January 28, 2017 |accessdate=January 28, 2017|website=MalcolmMusic}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2009\u201315: Career beginnings===\nIn 2009, Tory Lanez released his debut mixtape, ''T.L 2 T.O''.  While Lanez lived in [[South Florida]], he began directing some of his music videos, and posted them on his YouTube channel. [[Sean Kingston]] was interested in Lanez after seeing a video of him freestyling over [[Lloyd Banks]]' \"[[Beamer, Benz, or Bentley]]\".<ref name=\"Bajan\" /> In February 2010, Kingston contacted Lanez, telling him to meet up with him, during [[Justin Bieber]]'s tour and later got him to perform on there live.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=31c_LPqF1PI|date=January 24, 2011|title=History in the Making (Documentary) \u2013 Tory Lanez|accessdate=December 7, 2014}}</ref> In 2010, Lanez released the mixtapes, ''Just Landed, One Verse One Hearse, Playing for Keeps'' and ''Mr. 1 Verse Killah.'' In 2011, Lanez signed a record deal with Kingston's Time is Money Entertainment and released the mixtapes, ''Mr. Peterson, Chixtape,'' and ''Swavey''. He later left the label to be an independent artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/3295611-Tory-Lanez|title=Tory Lanez|publisher=discogs|access-date=May 25, 2016}}</ref> In 2012, Tory Lanez released the mixtape, ''Sincerely Tory, Conflicts of My Soul: The 416 Story'' in 2013, and ''Chixtape II'' in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.datpiff.com/Tory-Lanez-Sincerely-Tory-mixtape.351700.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Sincerely Tory|website=DatPiff|access-date=June 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/08/mixtape-premiere-tory-lanez-conflicts-of-my-soul-the-416-story|title=Mixtape Premiere: Tory Lanez \"Conflicts Of My Soul: The 416 Story\"|website=Complex|access-date=June 2, 2016}}</ref> In April 2014, Tory released two episodes of the \"Public Swave Announcement\", of behind the scenes of the \"These Things Happen Tour\" with [[G-Eazy]] and [[Rockie Fresh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-public-swave-announcement-episode-1-new-video.27593.html|title=Tory Lanez 'Public Swave Announcement' Episode 1 [New Video]|author=De Loen, Mike|date=April 16, 2014|accessdate=July 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-public-swave-announcement-episode-2-new-video.27733.html|title=Tory Lanez 'Public Swave Announcement' Episode 2 [New Video]|date=April 23, 2014|author=James, Nicolas|accessdate=July 7, 2015}}</ref> On June 2, 2014, Lanez released the song, \"Teyana\", as a tribute to singer [[Teyana Taylor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-teyana-new-song.1909077.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Teyana {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=June 2, 2016}}</ref> Taylor responded with the track, \"Dreams of Fuckin' an R&B Bitch\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://watchloud.com/teyana-taylor-responds-tory-lanez-track/|title=Teyana Taylor Responds To Tory Lanez With \u2018Dreams of F*ckin An R&B B*tch\u2019|author=Kymmi|date=September 26, 2014|accessdate=May 31, 2015|publisher=watchloud.com}}</ref> On June 6, 2014, Lanez released, \"The Godfather\", a song to announce that he was going to start a series called, ''Fargo Fridays'', only releasing songs, albums, or videos on Fridays on HotNewHipHop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-the-godfather-prod-by-playback-and-tory-lanez-new-song.1911343.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 The Godfather (Prod. By PlayBack & Tory Lanez) {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=June 2, 2016}}</ref> The songs, \"I'll Be There\", \"Talk On Road\", and \"Balenciagas\" were released later that month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-i-ll-be-there-feat-meek-mill-french-montana-new-song.1916311.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 I'll Be There Feat. Meek Mill & French Montana {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=June 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/torylanez/talk-on-road-prod-daniel-worthy-x-tory-lanez-x-the-mekanics|title=Talk On Road (Prod. The MeKanics x Daniel Worthy x Tory Lanez)|website=SoundCloud|access-date=June 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-balenciagas-prod-by-tory-lanez-and-play-picasso-new-song.1925308.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Balenciagas (Prod. By Tory Lanez & Play Picasso) {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=June 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter releasing a bunch of songs from the series, he released a song called, \"The Mission\" to celebrate his tour announcement on August 14, 2014. Lanez kicked off his first headlining tour, the \"Lost Cause Tour\", in conjunction with the mixtape, ''[[Lost Cause (Tory Lanez mixtape)|Lost Cause]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-the-mission-new-song.1956003.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 The Mission {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=June 2, 2016}}</ref> The mixtape was supposed to be released on September 29, 2014, but got pushed back to October 1. In an interview, Tory Lanez claimed he has ghost-written songs for artists such as [[Akon]] (\"[[Seen It All: The Autobiography|Been Gettin' Money]]\" with [[Jeezy]]), [[Casey Veggies]] (\"[[Live & Grow|Actin' Up]]\"), [[August Alsina]] (\"[[Dreams Worth More Than Money|My Niggas]]\" with Meek Mill), as well as [[T.I.]] and [[Travis Scott]].<ref>[http://genius.com/artists/tory-lanez] {{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-talks-teyana-taylor-lost-cause-and-toronto-s-music-scene-news.12565.html|title=Tory Lanez Talks Teyana Taylor, \"Lost Cause\", and Toronto Music Scene|date=October 22, 2014|author=Lyons, Patrick|accessdate=May 31, 2015}}</ref> On February 27, 2015, Tory Lanez revealed that he was going to release a collaboration EP with the WeDidIt Records producers on April 6.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2015/02/27/tory-lanez-henny-in-hand-1|title=Watch Tory Lanez' Video For \"Henny in Hand\"|date=February 27, 2015|website=[[The Fader]]|accessdate=May 31, 2015|author=Trammel, Matthew}}</ref> On April 3, 2015, Tory released the single titled \"In For It\" for his upcoming EP.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-in-for-it-prod-by-rl-grime-new-song.1963835.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 In For It (Prod. By RL Grime)|date=April 3, 2015|accessdate=May 10, 2015|author=Lyons, Patrick}}</ref> On May 8, 2015, Lanez released another song, titled \"Ric Flair\" featuring Rory Trustory. On May 22, 2015, he released the second single for the EP, titled \"Acting Like\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-acting-like-prod-by-shlohmo-new-song.1964595.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Acting Like (Prod. By Shlohmo) &#124; Stream & Listen [New Song]|date=May 22, 2015|accessdate=May 31, 2015|author=Lilah, Rose}}</ref> On June 19, 2015, Tory announced that the EP would be called, ''[[Cruel Intentions (album)|Cruel Intentions]]'' and released on June 26, 2015. That same day the single, \"[[Karrueche Tran|Karrueche]]\" was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-karrueche-prod-by-noah-breakfast-new-song.1965033.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Karrueche (Prod. By Noah Breakfast) &#124; Stream & Listen [New Song]|date=June 19, 2015|website=hotnewhiphop.com|accessdate=June 20, 2015|author=Lilah, Rose}}</ref>\n\n=== 2015\u2013present: ''I Told You'', ''Memories Don't Die'', ''Love Me Now'', ''Chixtape 5'' and ''The New Toronto 3'' ===\nOn July 15, 2015, Tory Lanez released the first single off his debut album, titled \"[[Say It (Tory Lanez song)|Say It]]\". It was also revealed that he signed to [[Benny Blanco]]'s [[Benny Blanco#Record Labels|Mad Love Records]] and [[Interscope Records]]. On September 18, 2015, Lanez released the single, \"[[B.L.O.W. (song)|BLOW]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-blow-new-song.1966344.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 B.L.O.W. (Prod. By Play Picasso & Sergio R) {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=March 11, 2016}}</ref> December 25, 2015, Lanez released the two mixtapes, ''[[Chixtape III]]'' and ''[[The New Toronto]]''. On January 18, 2016, \"[[LA Confidential (song)|LA Confidential]]\" was released as the second single for the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-la-confidential-new-song.1968319.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 LA Confidential {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=March 12, 2016}}</ref> On January 28, 2016, Tory Lanez made a guest appearance on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' By performing \"Say It\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-performs-say-it-with-brownstone-on-jimmy-kimmel-live-new-video.36649.html|title=Tory Lanez Performs 'Say It' With Brownstone On Jimmy Kimmel Live!|date=January 28, 2016|accessdate=March 14, 2016|website=HotNewHipHop|author=Walker, Angus}}</ref> A month later, Lanez released a remix of [[MadeinTYO]]'s \"[[Uber Everywhere]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-uber-everywhere-new-song.1968717.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Uber Everywhere  {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=March 12, 2016}}</ref> On March 4, 2016, Lanez released the song, \"Tim Duncan\" as a part of his ''Fargo Fridays'' series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-tim-duncan-prod-by-c-sick-new-song.1968824.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Tim Duncan (Prod. By C-Sick) {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=March 12, 2016}}</ref> He released the song, \"Real Addresses\" the next week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-real-addresses-new-song.1968916.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Real Addresses {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=March 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, 2016, [[ASAP Ferg]] and Tory Lanez announced \"The Level Up Tour\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/asap-ferg-and-tory-lanez-announce-the-level-up-tour-news.20883.html|title=ASAP Ferg & Tory Lanez Announce \"The Level Up Tour\"|last=Schwartz|first=Danny|date=April 1, 2016|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=April 9, 2016}}</ref> On April 5, 2016, it was revealed that Tory Lanez would perform at [[Summer Jam]] and [[Pemberton Music Festival]] in the summer of 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/summer-jam-festival-stage-line-up-includes-chance-the-rapper-tory-lanez-and-desiigner-news.20935.html|title=Summer Jam Festival Stage Line-Up Includes Chance The Rapper, Tory Lanez & Desiigner|last=Lilah|first=Rose|date=April 5, 2016|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=April 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/j-cole-snoop-dogg-wiz-khalifa-and-ice-cube-to-headline-pemberton-2016-news.20945.html|title=J. Cole, Snoop Dogg, Wiz Khalifa, & Ice Cube To Headline Pemberton 2016|last=Schwartz|first=Danny|date=April 5, 2016|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=April 9, 2016}}</ref> On April 8, 2016, Tory Lanez and ASAP Ferg collaborated on the song, \"Line Up the Flex\" to promote their \"Level Up\" tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-and-asap-ferg-line-up-the-flex-prod-by-play-picasso-new-song.1969314.html|title=Tory Lanez & A$AP Ferg \u2013 Line Up The Flex (Prod. By Play Picasso) &#124; Stream [New Song]|last=Lilah|first=Rose|date=April 8, 2016|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=April 9, 2016}}</ref> On April 18, Tory Lanez refused to be on the 2016 XXL Freshmen cover because he felt he was in a higher league musically than the other artists being considered.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.designntrend.com/articles/74225/20160418/tory-lanez-refuses-2016-xxl-freshman-cover-pulls-himself-out.htm|title=Tory Lanez Refuses To Be On 2016 XXL Freshman Cover, Pulls Himself Out: 'Don't Be Confused'|date=April 18, 2016|website=Design & Trend|access-date=May 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/04/tory-lanez-shots-at-drake/|title=Five Times Tory Lanez Took Shots at Drake|last=Weinstein|first=Max|date=April 18, 2016|website=XXL|access-date=May 16, 2016}}</ref> On May 6, 2016, Lanez released two songs, \"For Real\" and \"Unforgetful\" as a part of the ''Fargo Friday'' series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-for-real-new-song.1969672.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 For Real {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=May 9, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-unforgetful-prod-by-london-on-da-track-new-song.1969674.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Unforgetful (Prod. By London On Da Track) {{!}} Stream [New Song]|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=May 9, 2016}}</ref> On July 29, 2016, Lanez released the official second single \"[[Luv (Tory Lanez song)|Luv]]\" on [[iTunes]]. He also revealed that his album title would be ''[[I Told You]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-luv-prod-by-benny-blanco-and-cashmere-cat-new-song.1970139.html|title=Tory Lanez \u2013 Luv (Prod. By Benny Blanco & Cashmere Cat) &#124; Stream [New Song]|last=Lilah|first=Rose|date=June 10, 2016|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=June 10, 2016}}</ref> ''I Told You'' was released on August 19, 2016. On July 5, Lanez released two remixes for [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]'s \"[[Controlla]]\" and [[DJ Khaled]]'s \"[[I Got the Keys]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/66703-tory-lanez-remixes-drakes-controlla-listen/|title=Tory Lanez Remixes Drake's \"Controlla\": Listen|last=Lozano|first=Kevin|date=July 10, 2016|website=[[Pitchfork Media]]|access-date=July 23, 2016}}</ref> On July 20, Lanez announced the I Told You tour to promote the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.39692/title.tory-lanez-announces-album-release-date-tour|title=Tory Lanez Announces Album Release Date & Tour|last=Mitchell|first=Chris|date=July 20, 2016|website=HipHopDX|access-date=July 23, 2016}}</ref>\nOn March 2, 2018, Lanez released his second studio album, ''[[Memories Don't Die]]''. Within the same year, he has also released an album titled ''[[Love Me Now? (album)|Love Me Now?]]'' on October 26, 2018,<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-shares-love-me-now-release-date-and-cover-art-news.62067.html |title=Tory Lanez Shares \"Love Me Now\" Release Date & Cover Art |website=Hotnewhiphop.com |date=2018-10-12 |accessdate=2020-04-16}}</ref> He also released an album titled ''[[Chixtape 5]]'' on November 15, 2019, and another album titled ''[[The New Toronto 3]]'' on April 10, 2020.<ref>{{cite|url=https://www.nme.com/big-reads/tory-lanez-cover-interview-2020-words-are-so-powerful-death-and-life-is-in-the-power-of-your-tongue-2624318|title=Tory Lanez: \u201cWords are so powerful. Death and life is in the power of your tongue\u201d|website=NME|last=Perry|first=Kevin EG|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, 2020, Lanez teamed up with Jamaican [[reggae]] singer [[Buju Banton]] for a remix of \"Trust\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dancehallmag.com/2020/03/20/music/epic-fail-for-buju-bantons-trust-remix-with-tory-lanez.html|title=Epic Fail For Buju Banton's \u2018Trust\u2019 Remix With Tory Lanez|date=March 20, 2020|website=dancehallmag.com|accessdate=March 21, 2020|author=Baugh, Claudine}}</ref>\n\n== Musical style ==\nIn an interview on Nice Kicks with Ian Stonebook, Lanez described his own personal style he calls, Swavey: \"Swavey is a two-adjective word. A lot of people use it as an attribute, but the real definition of swavey is a genre of music. The genre of music is the genre of fusing more than one together. I know it sounds strange, but if you ask an artist what they do they're going to say that they rap, they sing, they do rock, a lot of people are multi-talented. They get looked at confused, but I don't think that they're confused. I feel that they're just talented, swavey artists. Labels want to put you in one lane, but I feel like there are so many people are more than that and they're swavey artists.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nicekicks.com/2012/10/14/tory-lanez-talks-air-jordans-music-industry-advice-staying-swavey/|title=Tory Lanez Talks Air Jordans, Music Industry Advice & Staying Swavey &#124; Nice Kicks|date=October 14, 2012|accessdate=July 7, 2015|author=Stonebook, Ian}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n\n===Drake===\nIn 2010, Lanez posted a video on YouTube, challenging fellow Canadian [[rapper]] [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]], to whom he was rumored to be related. The video features him denying these rumors and announcing the $10,000 challenge. While showing Drake respect, Lanez again challenged him, but only if Drake would listen to some of his tracks from his second mixtape ''Playing for Keeps''. Lanez also claimed that if Drake did not like it, he would personally give to him $10,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://torylanez.wordpress.com/about/|title=Biography The Official Tory Lanez Fansite|accessdate=December 3, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://drizzy.ning.com/m/discussion?id=3514281%3ATopic%3A110007|title=Tory Lanez $10,000 Challenge To Drake (Who Do Ya'll Think?)|date=March 27, 2010|author=Kevin G|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref> In August 2015, while appearing on the \"Sway in the Morning\" radio show on [[Shade 45]], Lanez had taken a shot at Drake, alluding to the infamous freestyle he had performed on [[Hot 97]] six years prior where he had read lyrics from his [[BlackBerry]]. In October 2015, Lanez created additional tension with the rapper when he expressed his dislike of the use of \"the 6\", a nickname for Toronto, and one that had, of course, been popularized by Drake.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rapdose.com/2015/10/12/tory-lanez-disses-drake-says-its-not-cool-to-call-toronto-the-6/|title=Tory Lanez Disses Drake, Says It's Not Cool To Call Toronto \"The 6\"|website=Rapdose.com|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the lyrics of his 2016 single \"[[Summer Sixteen]]\", Drake appears to make a subliminal diss at Lanez, rapping: \"All you boys in the new Toronto want to be me a little.\" Many took this, and the ensuing lines, to be something off a shot taken towards Tory Lanez. Drake also took aim at [[Meek Mill]] who, in the midst of their ongoing feud, called out Drake for dissing Lanez on the song, \"[[War Pain]]\": \"Tory from the 6, you hatin\u2019 on him, Lord knows!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/drake-goes-after-meek-mill-barack-obama-and-tory-lanez-on-summer-sixteen-news.19888.html|title=Drake Goes After Meek Mill, Barack Obama & Tory Lanez On \"Summer Sixteen\"|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=March 12, 2016}}</ref> In an interview with [[Revolt (TV network)|Revolt]], Tory was asked about the perceived shot. He was skeptical about whether it was aimed at him at all, he assured the press that he wouldn't be responding even if it was. \"Drake could diss me 20,000 times, and I\u2019d never diss him. I\u2019m a fan... I have no negativity on my side. All blessings to that man.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-on-drake-id-never-diss-him-im-a-fan-news.20159.html|title=Tory Lanez On Drake: \"I'd Never Diss Him \u2013 I'm A Fan\"|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=March 12, 2016}}</ref> When Tory released his version of, \"Uber Everywhere\", he raps, \"Pussy boy, smack that smile clean off your face / You don't know no trap niggas, you don't be around this way / You some actor nigga boy, I used to see you on the screen\". Many people thought Tory was taking shots at Drake. Tory disses Drake again in the song, \"Line Up the Flex\" with ASAP Ferg. Lanez rapped \"I was never gang, gang, gang, gang/ I was One Umbrella Mob\", in a response to Drake's shot at him on \"Summer Sixteen\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDrake fired back in the song, \"Still Here\" on the album, [[Views (album)|''Views'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/04/drake-views-from-the-6-album-subliminal-shots/|title=10 Subliminal Shots on Drake's 'Views' Album \u2013 XXL|website=XXL Mag|access-date=May 17, 2016}}</ref> In an interview with [[Zane Lowe]] on [[Beats 1]], Drake spoke on Tory: \"I encourage anybody to go out there and do the most damage that you possibly can. Do you things. Get all the fruits. Get everything. Become the biggest artist you can possibly be. Just don't get up there finally and start talking down on me, especially when we have no interaction.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.designntrend.com/articles/75288/20160502/drake-talks-torey-lanez-beef-blasts-young-rappper-trying-diss.htm|title=Drake Talks Torey Lanez Beef, Blasts Young Rapper For Trying To Diss Him|last=Nelson|first=Daryl|date=May 2, 2016|website=Design & Trend|access-date=May 16, 2016}}</ref> Tory took shots at Drake again in the song, \"For Real\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/new-music/2016/05/tory-lanez-drake-shots-for-real/|title=Tory Lanez Baits Drake Once More With Shots on 'For Real'|last=Ivey|first=Justin|date=May 6, 2016|website=XXL|access-date=May 16, 2016}}</ref> On June 27, 2016, Lanez talked to Ebro on the Ebro in the Morning show and he stated about [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]] and said \"Hip-hop is a contact sport, I'm here to compete, I'm here to be #1.\" He goes on to say, \"I was a fan of his music before, no one's ever took that from me. That doesn't mean I'm not here to take my crown.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-on-drake-we-cant-share-first-place-news.22509.html?|title=Ready to take crown|last=Lilah|first=Rose|date=June 27, 2016|website=Hotnewhiphop|access-date=June 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Jacquees===\nIn February 2016, [[Jacquees]] tweeted, \"[[Chris Brown|Chris [Brown]]] my idol/big bro he don't count never will but you other guys im at yo throat #FuckHowYouFeel\". The tweet meant that Jacquees is in a fierce competition with every [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] artist in the game, except for [[Chris Brown]], who he says is his idol. The tweet wasn't convincing to Lanez, who responded to Jacquees with two choice emojis. Jacquees took Lanez' emoji response as an assault, and he went on to call Lanez a \"peasant\" and \"watermelon head ass\". Jacquees did, however, take the time to compliment Lanez' penmanship, though he implied that Lanez' vocal talents are not up to par with his own. Lanez still hasn't responded to Jacquees, but tells his fans to \"advise that boy\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/jacquees-challenges-randb-competition-tory-lanez-responds-news.20366.html|title=Jacquees Challenges R&B Competition, Tory Lanez Responds|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=March 12, 2016}}</ref> The two later squashed their beef at [[South by Southwest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-and-jacquees-have-squashed-their-beef-news.20683.html|title=Tory Lanez & Jacquees Have Squashed Their Beef|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=March 20, 2016}}</ref> They later announced in August 2016 that they were going on tour together.\n\n=== Joyner Lucas ===\nIn November 2018, during an [[Instagram]] Live session, Lanez claimed that he's a better rapper than American rapper [[Joyner Lucas]].<ref name=\"Jahmal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-is-resurrecting-friendly-competition-in-hip-hop-news.70768.html|title=Tory Lanez Is Resurrecting Friendly Competition in Hip-Hop|last=Jahmal|first=Karlton|date=n.d.|website=HotNewHipHop|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 12, 2019}}</ref> In response, Lucas challenged Lanez to a [[Battle rap|rap battle]], which led to several diss records being released between the two, including the \"[[Lucky You (song)|Lucky You]] Freestyle\" and the \"[[Zeze (song)|Zeze]] Freestyle\".<ref name=\"Jahmal\"/> Although the beef was short lived, Lanez expressed distaste at those who sided with Lucas.<ref name=\"Jahmal\"/> The end of the beef was once more evident when the two released a remix of [[DaBaby]]'s song [[Suge (DaBaby song)|Suge]].\n\n=== Don Q ===\nShortly after his beef with Joyner Lucas ensued, New York rapper [[Don Q (rapper)|Don Q]] dropped a battle track titled \"I'm Not Joyner\", alleging that Lanez was stealing Q's lyrics.<ref name=\"Jahmal\"/> Lanez fired back with a track called \"Dom Queen\", before Q responded with another diss track.<ref name=\"Jahmal\"/> Another rapper, [[Dreamville Records|Dreamville]] artist [[JID]] was involved into the beef, seemingly displeased with previous statements Lanez made aimed at his mentor, [[J. Cole]].<ref name=\"Jahmal\"/> Lanez then challenged the entire Dreamville artist roster in response, with rappers including Dreamdoll responding with their own tracks aimed at Lanez.<ref name=\"Jahmal\"/>\n\n=== Response ===\nIn response to Tory Lanez's various rap beefs, Karlton Jahmal of Hip-hop publication ''HotNewHipHop'' said \"the art of the competitive, lyrical battle rap has been missing from the mainstream wave for years...\", until Lanez brought the culture exactly what it's been missing with his friendly yet competitive take. Jahmal concluded that Lanez was essentially \"engineering an overall shift back to the roots of hip-hop [...] more about proving lyrical talent than they are about utterly destroying an opponent\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-is-resurrecting-friendly-competition-in-hip-hop-news.70768.html|title=Tory Lanez Is Resurrecting Friendly Competition in Hip-Hop|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=July 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Legal issues==\nOn March 26, 2016, during a concert in [[Midland, Texas]], violent scuffles between security forces and concertgoers occurred. Lanez then proceeded to tell the crowd to \"fuck shit up,\" which incited a full-on riot and forced police to shut down the show. Multiple people were arrested. The venue and concert promoters are considering legal actions against Lanez.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.38087/title.tory-lanez-incites-riot-cops-shut-down-texas-concert|title=Tory Lanez Incites Riot & Cops Shut Down Texas Concert|last=Hernandez|first=Victoria|date=March 28, 2016|website=[[HipHopDX]]|access-date=April 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Tory Lanez discography}}\n* ''[[I Told You]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Memories Don't Die]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Love Me Now?]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Chixtape 5]]'' (2019) \n* ''[[The New Toronto 3]]'' (2020)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Awards\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n|2015\n|[[2015 Much Music Video Awards|Much Music Video Awards]]\n|[[MuchMusic Video Award for Best Rap Video|Best Hip Hop Video]]\n|\"Henny in Hand\"\n|rowspan=\"8\" {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|2016\n|[[BET Awards 2016|BET Awards]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.39389/title.the-full-list-of-bet-award-winners-2016 | title=The Full List Of BET Award Winners 2016 | work=[[HipHopDX]] | date=June 26, 2016 | accessdate=August 22, 2016}}</ref>\n|[[BET Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|Himself\n|-\n|[[2016 BET Hip Hop Awards|BET Hip Hop Awards]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.complex.com/music/2016/08/bet-hip-hop-awards-2016-nominees | title=Here Are the Nominees for BET's 2016 Hip-Hop Awards | work=Complex | date=August 18, 2016 | accessdate=August 22, 2016}}</ref>\n|Best New Hip Hop Artist\n|-\n| [[MOBO Awards]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.glasgowlive.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/mobo-awards-2016-nominations-announced-11916262 | title=MOBO Awards 2016 nominations announced: Find out who made the shortlist | work=Glasgow Live | date=September 21, 2016 | accessdate=September 21, 2016}}</ref>\n| Best International Act\n|-\n| [[2016 Soul Train Music Awards|Soul Train Music Awards]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rap-up.com/2016/10/12/drake-leads-soul-train-awards-2016-nominations/ | title=Drake Leads Soul Train Awards 2016 Nominations | work=Rap-Up | date=October 12, 2016 | accessdate=October 13, 2016}}</ref>\n| [[Soul Train Music Award for Best R&B/Soul or Rap New Artist|Best New Artist]]\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2017\n| [[59th Annual Grammy Awards|Grammy Awards]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7597556/grammys-nominees-complete-list-2017 | title=Here Is the Complete List of Nominees for the 2017 Grammys | work=Billboard | date=December 6, 2016 | accessdate=December 6, 2016}}</ref>\n| [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Song|Best R&B Song]]\n| \"[[Luv (Tory Lanez song)|Luv]]\"\n|-\n| rowspan=3|[[Juno Awards of 2017|Juno Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Juno Awards Nominees 2017: Here's the Full Nominations List|url=http://www.flare.com/celebrity/entertainment/juno-awards-nominees-2017/|website=Flare|accessdate=March 13, 2017|date=February 7, 2017}}</ref>\n| Fan Choice Award\n| rowspan=2|Himself\n|-\n| Breakthrough Artist of the Year\n|-\n| Rap Recording of the Year\n| \"Shooters\"\n|{{won}}<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/music/junos/news/junos-2018-the-complete-list-of-winners-1.4579405 \"Junos 2018: the complete list of winners\"]. CBC News,  \u00b7 March 25, 2018</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|2019\n|[[50th NAACP Image Awards|NAACP Image Awards]]\n|Best New Artist\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Himself\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3|[[Juno Awards of 2019|Juno Awards]]\n| Fan Choice Award\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{nom}}\n|-\n| Artist of the Year\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Juno Award for Rap Recording of the Year|Rap Recording]]\n|''Love Me Now?''\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|2019\n|[[2019 BET Hip Hop Awards|BET Hip Hop Awards]]\n|Best International Flow \n|rowspan=\"3\"|Himself\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3|[[Juno Awards of 2020|Juno Awards]]\n| Fan Choice Award\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{Pending}}\n|-\n| Artist of the Year\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{Pending}}\n|-\n| [[Juno Award for Rap Recording of the Year|Rap Recording]]\n|''Freaky''\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{Pending}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|2020\n|[[Juno Awards]]\n|[[Juno Award for R&B/Soul Recording of the Year]]\n|''Chixtape 5''\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{Pending}}\n|-\n|[[Juno Awards]]\n|[[Juno Award for R&B/Soul Recording of the Year]]\n|''Feel It Too''\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{Pending}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{SoundCloud}}\n*{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=mn0002775792}}\n\n{{Tory Lanez}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lanez, Tory}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Black Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Barbadian descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Cura\u00e7aoan descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian male rappers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian rappers]]\n[[Category:Interscope Records artists]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Rap Recording of the Year winners]]\n", "name_user": "Liltomvil", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tory_Lanez"}
{"title_page": "Oliver St John, 1st Viscount Grandison", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n\n[[File:Oliver St John.jpg|thumb|Oliver St John, 1st Viscount Grandison, 1st Baron Tregoz]]\n\n'''Sir Oliver St John, 1st Viscount Grandison''' (1559 \u2013 30 December 1630) was an English soldier  and  politician who became [[Lord Deputy of Ireland]].\n\n==Early years==\nHe was the second son of [[Nicholas St John]] (ca. 1526 \u2013 8 November 1589) of [[Lydiard Park]] in Wiltshire and [[Purley Park]] in Berkshire, by his wife Elizabeth (bef. 1542 \u2013 1587), daughter of Sir Richard Blount of [[Mapledurham House]] in Oxfordshire, and Elizabeth Lister. His mother was distantly related to [[Charles Blount, 8th Baron Mountjoy]], and on his father's side he was descended through a female line from the Grandisons, and was related to the [[Margaret Beauchamp of Bletso|St Johns, Barons of Bletso]]. He seems to have grown up mostly at [[Purley-on-Thames|Purley]],<ref>[http://www.berkshirehistory.com/villages/purley.html Royal Berkshire History: Purley]</ref>  and was educated at Oxford, matriculating from [[Trinity College, Oxford|Trinity College]] on 20 December 1577, and graduating B.A. on 26 June 1578.  Knowing that his father, who expected him to make his own way,  would leave him very little money, he decided on a career in the law. In 1580 he was admitted a student of [[Lincoln's Inn]]; but about March 1584 he killed the  well-known  [[explorer]]  [[George Best (chronicler)|George Best]] in a [[duel]] and was compelled to flee the country. The motive for the duel  is unclear, although St John's violent temper no doubt contributed to it: by his own  later admission he was \"by nature the child of wrath\".\n\n==Career==\nSt John now sought his fortunes as a soldier abroad, and served in [[Flanders]] and in France. Before 1591 he had attained the rank of captain, and in the autumn of that year commanded [[Robert Devereux, 2nd Earl of Essex|Essex's]] horse at the siege of [[Rouen]]. In 1592 he returned to England, and was elected member for [[Cirencester (UK Parliament constituency)|Cirencester]] in the parliament summoned to meet on 19 February 1593. In March he was placed on a commission for the relief of maimed soldiers and mariners, and made several speeches during the session; but parliament was dissolved in April, and soon afterwards Essex recommended St John to [[Robert Cecil, 1st Earl of Salisbury|Robert Cecil]] as a cavalryman. He again sought service in the Netherlands, and was present at the [[battle of Nieuport]] on 2 July 1600.\n\n===Ireland===\n\n[[Tyrone's rebellion]] took experienced English soldiers to Ireland, and St John accompanied Mountjoy there in February 1601; he was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] by Mountjoy at Dublin on 28 February, and was given command of two hundred men. He took a prominent part in the [[siege of Kinsale]] in the autumn, repulsing a night attack of the Spanish on 2 December, when he was wounded. On 13 December he left the camp to carry despatches to Queen Elizabeth. In November 1602 he was back in Ireland commanding twenty-five horse and 150-foot in [[Connacht|Connaught]], under [[George Carew, 1st Earl of Totnes|Sir George Carew]], and in the same year he was recommended by Cecil for the office of vice-president of that province (but the arrangement does not seem to have been carried out). From 1604 to 1607 he sat in the English parliament as member for [[Portsmouth (UK Parliament constituency)|Portsmouth]]. On 12 December 1605 he was made master of the ordnance in Ireland, and sworn of the Irish privy council.\n\nFrom this time St John was [[Arthur Chichester, 1st Baron Chichester|Sir Arthur Chichester]]'s most trusted adviser. Early in 1608 he was named a commissioner for the [[plantation of Ulster]]. He drew up a scheme for the plantation of the province, and accompanied Chichester in his progress through Ulster in 1609. As an undertaker he had grants of fifteen hundred acres in [[Ballymore, County Armagh|Ballymore]], [[co. Armagh]], and a thousand acres (4&nbsp;km\u00b2) in 'Keernan. He advised that no grants of the lands of the  [[Flight of the Earls| banished Earls]]  should be made, but that they should be let to the  native Irish at a high rent. Early in 1609 Chichester sent him to England, and he drew up a report of the commissioners' proceedings for Salisbury's benefit.\n\n===Member of the Irish Parliament===\n\nIn 1613 he was elected member of the [[Parliament of Ireland|Irish Parliament]]  for [[County Roscommon (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|County Roscommon]], and took an important part in the dispute about the speakership,  which descended into pantomime after the  rival factions  chose Sir [[John Everard (MP)|John Everard]]  and Sir [[John Davies (poet)|John Davies]].  Speaking from his experience of the English House of Commons, St John  urged that the first business of the house was to elect a speaker, and that the proper method of voting was to leave the house and be counted in a lobby. Everard's supporters, however, placed Everard in the chair, from which he was only ejected by the majority after  Davies, a very fat man, actually sat on him.  St John was one of the members sent to lay the matter before James I: as a result Everard was summoned before the  Privy Council and  briefly imprisoned in the [[Tower of London]], before being sent home with an admonition.  In December 1614 St John resigned the mastership of the ordnance; he was in England during October 1615, when the [[Robert Carr, 1st Earl of Somerset|Earl of Somerset]] was committed to his custody, in connection with the [[murder]]  of [[Sir  Thomas  Overbury]].\n\n===Lord Deputy of Ireland===\n\nIn 1615 he was appointed [[Vice-Admiral of Connaught]] for life and confirmed in the position by [[George Villiers, 1st Duke of Buckingham|George Villiers, Duke of Buckingham]] in 1619. He surrendered the position in 1627.<ref> {{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930074029/http://www.history.ac.uk/office/viceadmirals2.html#ac|url=http://www.history.ac.uk/office/viceadmirals2.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 November 2016|title=Vice Admirals of the Coasts 1558\u20131660|publisher=Institute of Historical Research|accessdate=15 February 2019}} </ref>\n\nOn 2 July 1616 St John was appointed [[Lord Deputy of Ireland]]; he received the sword of state on 30 August. His appointment was partly due to his close  family connection with the Duke of Buckingham, by then the prime Royal Favourite, and his administration, like Chichester's was marked by persecution of [[recusants]]. He banished, by proclamation, all [[monks]]  and friars educated abroad. He also pushed on the colonisation of Ulster, and the plantation of [[co. Longford]] in 1618 was followed next year by that of [[co. Leitrim]]. His severity against the recusants created enemies, and the fact that he owed his appointment to Villiers made him unpopular with many of his council. Early in 1621 they urged his recall; and, though James commended him and protested against involving him in disgrace, he was finally commanded to deliver up the sword of state to  [[Adam Loftus, 1st Viscount Loftus|Lord Chancellor  Loftus]]  on 18 April 1622. He left Ireland on 4 May.\n\nSt John still remained in favour at court. On 28 June 1622 he was sworn of the English privy council, on 23 June 1623 he was created '''[[Viscount Grandison]]''' of Limerick in the [[peerage of Ireland]], on 16 August 1625 he was made [[Lord High Treasurer of Ireland]], and on 20 May 1626 was raised to the [[English peerage]] as '''Baron Tregoz''' of Highworth, Wiltshire.\n\nIn 1624 St John was placed on the Council of War, and served on other commissions. He also interested himself in foreign and colonial affairs, frequently corresponding with his nephew, [[Sir Thomas Roe]]. In 1627 he bought the manors of [[Wandsworth]] and [[Battersea]], where he had had a house since 1600. His health failing, he sought the advice of [[Sir Theodore Turquet de Mayerne]]. After a visit to Ireland in 1630 to settle his estates there, he returned to Battersea, where he died on 30 December in the same year, being buried there on 12 January 1631.\n\n==Family==\nSt John married Joan, daughter and heiress of John Roydon of [[Battersea]], and widow of Sir William Holcroft; she was buried at Battersea on 10 March 1631; by her he had no issue. The barony of Tregoz became extinct. Grandison's manors, [[Wandsworth]] and Battersea, passed to his nephew [[Sir John St John, 1st Baronet|Sir John St John]]. The viscounty of Grandison passed to his grand-nephew, [[William Villiers, 2nd Viscount Grandison|William Villiers]], son of [[Edward Villiers (Master of the Mint)|Sir Edward Villiers]] (who was the Duke of Buckingham's brother)  by his wife Barbara, younger daughter of Sir John St John, Grandison's elder brother.\n\n==References==\n*{{DNB|wstitle=St. John, Oliver (1559-1630)}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grandison, Oliver Saint John, 1st Viscount}}\n[[Category:1559 births]]\n[[Category:1630 deaths]]\n[[Category:English soldiers]]\n[[Category:Lords Lieutenant of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Viscounts in the Peerage of Ireland]]\n[[Category:People from Swindon]]\n[[Category:People from Battersea]]\n[[Category:People from West Berkshire District]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:People of Elizabethan Ireland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Ireland (pre-1801) for County Roscommon constituencies]]\n[[Category:Irish MPs 1613\u20131615]]\n[[Category:St John family]]\n[[Category:Duellists]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1593]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1604\u20131611]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n\n[[File:Oliver St John.jpg|thumb|Oliver St John, 1st Viscount Grandison, 1st Baron Tregoz]]\n\n'''Sir Oliver St John, 1st Viscount Grandison''' (1559 \u2013 30 December 1630) was an English soldier  and  politician who became [[Lord Deputy of Ireland]].\n\n==Early years==\nHe was the second son of [[Nicholas St John]] (ca. 1526 \u2013 8 November 1589) of [[Lydiard Park]] in Wiltshire and [[Purley Park]] in Berkshire, by his wife Elizabeth (bef. 1542 \u2013 1587), daughter of Sir Richard Blount of [[Mapledurham House]] in Oxfordshire, and Elizabeth Lister. His mother was distantly related to [[Charles Blount, 8th Baron Mountjoy]], and on his father's side he was descended through a female line from the Grandisons, and was related to the [[Margaret Beauchamp of Bletso|St Johns, Barons of Bletso]]. He seems to have grown up mostly at [[Purley-on-Thames|Purley]],<ref>[http://www.berkshirehistory.com/villages/purley.html Royal Berkshire History: Purley]</ref>  and was educated at Oxford, matriculating from [[Trinity College, Oxford|Trinity College]] on 20 December 1577, and graduating B.A. on 26 June 1578.  Knowing that his father, who expected him to make his own way,  would leave him very little money, he decided on a career in the law. In 1580 he was admitted a student of [[Lincoln's Inn]]; but about March 1584 he killed the  well-known  [[explorer]]  [[George Best (chronicler)|George Best]] in a [[duel]] and was compelled to flee the country. The motive for the duel  is unclear, although St John's violent temper no doubt contributed to it: by his own  later admission he was \"by nature the child of wrath\".\n\n==Career==\nSt John now sought his fortunes as a soldier abroad, and served in [[Flanders]] and in France. Before 1591 he had attained the rank of captain, and in the autumn of that year commanded [[Robert Devereux, 2nd Earl of Essex|Essex's]] horse at the siege of [[Rouen]]. In 1592 he returned to England, and was elected member for [[Cirencester (UK Parliament constituency)|Cirencester]] in the parliament summoned to meet on 19 February 1593. In March he was placed on a commission for the relief of maimed soldiers and mariners, and made several speeches during the session; but parliament was dissolved in April, and soon afterwards Essex recommended St John to [[Robert Cecil, 1st Earl of Salisbury|Robert Cecil]] as a cavalryman. He again sought service in the Netherlands, and was present at the [[battle of Nieuport]] on 2 July 1600.\n\n===Ireland===\n\n[[Tyrone's rebellion]] took experienced English soldiers to Ireland, and St John accompanied Mountjoy there in February 1601; he was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] by Mountjoy at Dublin on 28 February, and was given command of two hundred men. He took a prominent part in the [[siege of Kinsale]] in the autumn, repulsing a night attack of the Spanish on 2 December, when he was wounded. On 13 December he left the camp to carry despatches to Queen Elizabeth. In November 1602 he was back in Ireland commanding twenty-five horse and 150-foot in [[Connacht|Connaught]], under [[George Carew, 1st Earl of Totnes|Sir George Carew]], and in the same year he was recommended by Cecil for the office of vice-president of that province (but the arrangement does not seem to have been carried out). From 1604 to 1607 he sat in the English parliament as member for [[Portsmouth (UK Parliament constituency)|Portsmouth]]. On 12 December 1605 he was made master of the ordnance in Ireland, and sworn of the Irish privy council.\n\nFrom this time St. John was [[Arthur Chichester, 1st Baron Chichester|Sir Arthur Chichester]]'s most trusted adviser. Early in 1608 he was named a commissioner for the [[plantation of Ulster]]. He drew up a scheme for the plantation of the province, and accompanied Chichester in his progress through Ulster in 1609. As an undertaker he had grants of fifteen hundred acres in [[Ballymore, County Armagh|Ballymore]], [[co. Armagh]], and a thousand acres (4&nbsp;km\u00b2) in 'Keernan. He advised that no grants of the lands of the  [[Flight of the Earls| banished Earls]]  should be made, but that they should be let to the  native Irish at a high rent. Early in 1609 Chichester sent him to England, and he drew up a report of the commissioners' proceedings for Salisbury's benefit.\n\n===Member of the Irish Parliament===\n\nIn 1613 he was elected member of the [[Parliament of Ireland|Irish Parliament]]  for [[County Roscommon (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|County Roscommon]], and took an important part in the dispute about the speakership,  which descended into pantomime after the  rival factions  chose Sir [[John Everard (MP)|John Everard]]  and Sir [[John Davies (poet)|John Davies]].  Speaking from his experience of the English House of Commons, St. John  urged that the first business of the house was to elect a speaker, and that the proper method of voting was to leave the house and be counted in a lobby. Everard's supporters, however, placed Everard in the chair, from which he was only ejected by the majority after  Davies, a very fat man, actually sat on him.  St John was one of the members sent to lay the matter before James I: as a result Everard was summoned before the  Privy Council and  briefly imprisoned in the [[Tower of London]], before being sent home with an admonition.  In December 1614 St. John resigned the mastership of the ordnance; he was in England during October 1615, when the [[Robert Carr, 1st Earl of Somerset|Earl of Somerset]] was committed to his custody, in connection with the [[murder]]  of [[Sir  Thomas  Overbury]].\n\n===Lord Deputy of Ireland===\n\nIn 1615 he was appointed [[Vice-Admiral of Connaught]] for life and confirmed in the position by [[George Villiers, 1st Duke of Buckingham|George Villiers, Duke of Buckingham]] in 1619. He surrendered the position in 1627.<ref> {{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930074029/http://www.history.ac.uk/office/viceadmirals2.html#ac|url=http://www.history.ac.uk/office/viceadmirals2.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 November 2016|title=Vice Admirals of the Coasts 1558\u20131660|publisher=Institute of Historical Research|accessdate=15 February 2019}} </ref>\n\nOn 2 July 1616 St John was appointed [[Lord Deputy of Ireland]]; he received the sword of state on 30 August. His appointment was partly due to his close  family connection with the Duke of Buckingham, by then the prime Royal Favourite, and his administration, like Chichester's was marked by persecution of [[recusants]]. He banished, by proclamation, all [[monks]]  and friars educated abroad. He also pushed on the colonisation of Ulster, and the plantation of [[co. Longford]] in 1618 was followed next year by that of [[co. Leitrim]]. His severity against the recusants created enemies, and the fact that he owed his appointment to Villiers made him unpopular with many of his council. Early in 1621 they urged his recall; and, though James commended him and protested against involving him in disgrace, he was finally commanded to deliver up the sword of state to  [[Adam Loftus, 1st Viscount Loftus|Lord Chancellor  Loftus]]  on 18 April 1622. He left Ireland on 4 May.\n\nSt John still remained in favour at court. On 28 June 1622 he was sworn of the English privy council, on 23 June 1623 he was created '''[[Viscount Grandison]]''' of Limerick in the [[peerage of Ireland]], on 16 August 1625 he was made [[Lord High Treasurer of Ireland]], and on 20 May 1626 was raised to the [[English peerage]] as '''Baron Tregoz''' of Highworth, Wiltshire.\n\nIn 1624 St John was placed on the Council of War, and served on other commissions. He also interested himself in foreign and colonial affairs, frequently corresponding with his nephew, [[Sir Thomas Roe]]. In 1627 he bought the manors of [[Wandsworth]] and [[Battersea]], where he had had a house since 1600. His health failing, he sought the advice of [[Sir Theodore Turquet de Mayerne]]. After a visit to Ireland in 1630 to settle his estates there, he returned to Battersea, where he died on 30 December in the same year, being buried there on 12 January 1631.\n\n==Family==\nSt John married Joan, daughter and heiress of John Roydon of [[Battersea]], and widow of Sir William Holcroft; she was buried at Battersea on 10 March 1631; by her he had no issue. The barony of Tregoz became extinct. Grandison's manors, [[Wandsworth]] and Battersea, passed to his nephew [[Sir John St John, 1st Baronet|Sir John St John]]. The viscounty of Grandison passed to his grand-nephew, [[William Villiers, 2nd Viscount Grandison|William Villiers]], son of [[Edward Villiers (Master of the Mint)|Sir Edward Villiers]] (who was the Duke of Buckingham's brother)  by his wife Barbara, younger daughter of Sir John St John, Grandison's elder brother.\n\n==References==\n*{{DNB|wstitle=St. John, Oliver (1559-1630)}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grandison, Oliver Saint John, 1st Viscount}}\n[[Category:1559 births]]\n[[Category:1630 deaths]]\n[[Category:English soldiers]]\n[[Category:Lords Lieutenant of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Viscounts in the Peerage of Ireland]]\n[[Category:People from Swindon]]\n[[Category:People from Battersea]]\n[[Category:People from West Berkshire District]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:People of Elizabethan Ireland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Ireland (pre-1801) for County Roscommon constituencies]]\n[[Category:Irish MPs 1613\u20131615]]\n[[Category:St John family]]\n[[Category:Duellists]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1593]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1604\u20131611]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n", "name_user": "Julia H. Mach", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oliver_St_John,_1st_Viscount_Grandison"}
{"title_page": "Oka River", "text_new": "{{ref improve|date=April 2020}}\n{{About|a river in western Russia|the river in Siberia with the same name|Oka River (Siberia)|other uses|Oka (disambiguation){{!}}Oka}}\n{{Infobox river\n| name               = Oka\n| name_native        = \u041e\u043a\u0430\u0301\n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = \n| name_etymology     = \n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = NN Spit from Fedorovskogo Embankment 08-2016 img2.jpg\n| image_size         = 270\n| image_caption      = The Oka riverbank in [[Nizhny Novgorod]]\n| map                = Okarivermap.png\n| map_size           = 270\n| map_caption        = Map of the Volga watershed with the Oka highlighted\n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n<!---------------------- LOCATION -->\n| subdivision_type1  = Country\n| subdivision_name1  = [[Russia]]\n| subdivision_type2  = \n| subdivision_name2  = \n| subdivision_type3  = \n| subdivision_name3  = \n| subdivision_type4  = \n| subdivision_name4  = \n| subdivision_type5  = Cities\n| subdivision_name5  = [[Oryol]], [[Kaluga]], [[Serpukhov]], [[Kolomna]], [[Ryazan]], [[Murom]], [[Dzerzhinsk, Russia|Dzerzhinsk]], [[Nizhny Novgorod]]\n<!---------------------- PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS -->\n| length             = {{convert|1500|km|mi|abbr=on}} \n| width_min          = \n| width_avg          = \n| width_max          = \n| depth_min          = \n| depth_avg          = \n| depth_max          = \n| discharge1_location= \n| discharge1_min     = \n| discharge1_avg     = {{convert|1260|m3/s|cuft/s|abbr=on}}\n| discharge1_max     = \n<!---------------------- BASIN FEATURES -->\n| source1            = \n| source1_location   = [[Oryol Oblast]]\n| source1_coordinates= {{coord|52|21|45|N|36|13|20|E|display=inline}}\n| source1_elevation  = {{convert|226|m|abbr=on}}\n| mouth              = [[Volga River]]\n| mouth_location     = [[Nizhny Novgorod]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = {{coord|56|19|55|N|43|58|53|E|display=inline,title}}\n| mouth_elevation    = {{convert|67|m|abbr=on}}\n| progression        = {{RVolga}}\n| river_system       = \n| basin_size         = {{convert|245000|km2|abbr=on}}\n| tributaries_left   = \n| tributaries_right  = \n| custom_label       = \n| custom_data        = \n| extra              = \n}}\n\n'''Oka''' ({{lang-ru|\u041e\u043a\u0430\u0301}}, {{IPA-ru|\u0250\u02c8ka|IPA}}) is a river in central [[Russia]], the largest right [[tributary]] of the [[Volga]]. It flows through the regions of [[Oryol Oblast|Oryol]], [[Tula Oblast|Tula]], [[Kaluga Oblast|Kaluga]], [[Moscow Oblast|Moscow]], [[Ryazan Oblast|Ryazan]], [[Vladimir Oblast|Vladimir]] and [[Nizhny Novgorod Oblast|Nizhny Novgorod]] and is navigable over a large part of its total length, as far upstream as to the town of [[Kaluga]]. Its length is {{convert|1500|km|abbr=on}} and its catchment area is {{convert|245000|km2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=gvr>[http://textual.ru/gvr/index.php?card=177924 \u00ab\u0420\u0435\u043a\u0430 \u041e\u043a\u0430\u00bb], Russian State Water Registry</ref> The Russian capital [[Moscow]] sits on one of the Oka's tributaries&mdash;the [[Moskva River]].\n\n== Name and history ==\nThe Oka river was the homeland of the Eastern Slavic [[Vyatichi]] tribe.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=ktyM07I9HXwC&pg=PT36&lpg=PT36&dq=eastern+slavs+volga+homeland&source=bl&ots=y7TaAaSKS6&sig=ACfU3U1vtKvEHqbTB67TLcOOQEfoGfbTaQ&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjf4_eU9-TgAhWJDuwKHeOyBfMQ6AEwCXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Ukraine: A History, 4th Edition|last=Subtelny|first=Orest|date=2009-11-10|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=9781442697287|language=en}}</ref> By the 5th century the land around the Oka river was inhabited by different Slavic tribes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mouzenidis.com/russia/article/history-of-russia|title=History of Russia, the Russian Empire, in ancient times, read {{!}} we know everything - Mouzenidis Travel|work=Mouzenidis Travel|access-date=2018-11-18|language=en}}</ref>{{better source|date=April 2020}} The Baltic tribe of [[Galindians]] also lived in the western part of the Oka basin.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tarasov|first=\u0418\u043b\u044c\u044f \u0422\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432 / Ilia|title=\u0411\u0430\u043b\u0442\u044b \u0432 \u043c\u0438\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432. \u0413\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0434\u044b // \u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0442, \u2116 3-4, 2017. \u0421. 95-124.|url=https://www.academia.edu/37147068/%D0%91%D0%B0%D0%BB%D1%82%D1%8B_%D0%B2_%D0%BC%D0%B8%D0%B3%D1%80%D0%B0%D1%86%D0%B8%D1%8F%D1%85_%D0%92%D0%B5%D0%BB%D0%B8%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%B3%D0%BE_%D0%BF%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B5%D1%81%D0%B5%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%8F_%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%B4%D0%BE%D0%B2._%D0%93%D0%B0%D0%BB%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B4%D1%8B_%D0%98%D1%81%D1%82%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%B8%D1%87%D0%B5%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B8%D0%B9_%D1%84%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%BC%D0%B0%D1%82_3-4_2017._%D0%A1._95-124|journal=\u0411\u0430\u043b\u0442\u044b \u0432 \u043c\u0438\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432. \u0413\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0434\u044b|language=en}}</ref> Turkic tribes also inhabited the Oka area. The Oka river was also inhabited by Vikings and other peoples from Scandinavia.{{cn|date=April 2020}} Artifacts of Scandinavian origin were found along the Oka - Volga route.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=yUV-AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT892&lpg=PT892&dq=along+the+volga+waterway+scandinavian+artefacts&source=bl&ots=-PxRctP2Zn&sig=ACfU3U0y8eah4puHeGp5Fi1nmewigfEWIg&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwikysHIodLhAhWQJlAKHWR6AOYQ6AEwAHoECAYQAQ#v=onepage&q=along%20the%20volga%20waterway%20scandinavian%20artefacts&f=false|title=The Viking World|last=Brink|first=Stefan|last2=Price|first2=Neil|date=2008-10-31|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134318254|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Threads of Empire: Loyalty and Tsarist Authority in Bashkiria, 1552-1917|last=Steinwedel|first=Charles|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2016|isbn=|location=|pages=13}}</ref> There is no consensus opinion where the name Oka originated from.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nFrom the Mongol conquest until about 1633, the Oka was the last line of defense against steppe raiders. Later [[Zasechnaya cherta]], a chain of fortification lines, was created to protect [[Grand Duchy of Moscow]] and later the [[Tsardom of Russia]] from the [[Crimean\u2013Nogai slave raids in Eastern Europe|Crimean-Nogai Raids]]. It was south of the original line along the Oka River.\n\nThe river gave its name to the [[Upper Oka Principalities]], situated upstream from [[Tarusa]]. In 1221 Grand Duke [[Yuri II of Vladimir]] founded [[Nizhny Novgorod]], later to become one of largest Russian cities, to protect the Oka's confluence with the Volga. The [[Qasim Khanate]], a Muslim polity, occupied the middle reaches of the Oka (around the city of [[Kasimov]]) in the 15th and 16th centuries.\n\nBefore the construction of the railways in the mid-19th century and the building of the [[Moscow Canal]] in the 1930s, the Oka, along with its tributary [[Moscow River|Moskva]], served as an important transportation route connecting [[Moscow]] with the Volga River. Due to the Oka's and Moskva's meandering courses, travel was not particularly fast: for example, it took [[Cornelis de Bruijn]] around 10 days to sail from Moscow down these two rivers to Nizhny Novgorod in 1703.<ref>{{citation\n|first=Cornelis de |last=Bruin\n|title=Voyage au Levant: c'est-\u00e0-dire, dans les principaux endroits de l'Asie Mineure, dans les isles de Chio, Rhodes, Chypre, etc., de m\u00eame que dans les plus consid\u00e9rables villes d'Egypte, de Syrie, et Terre Sainte.\n|volume=3\n|publisher=J.-B.-C. Bauche le fils|year= 1725\n|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=ctUWAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA250|pages=233\u2013247}}\n</ref> Traveling upstream may have been even slower, as the boats had to be pulled by [[burlaks]].<ref>{{harvnb|Bruin|1725|p=240}}</ref>\n\n== Landmarks ==\nThe banks of the river are dotted with historical and cultural sites, including the medieval monasteries of [[Murom]], the mosques and minarets of [[Kasimov]], the fortified [[Kremlin (fortification)|kremlin]]s of [[Kolomna]] and [[Serpukhov]], the memorial houses of [[Vasily Polenov]] and [[Sergey Yesenin]], the excavated ruins of [[Old Ryazan]] and the [[Shukhov tower on the Oka River|Oka Shukhov Tower]].\n\nThe [[Prioksko-Terrasny Biosphere Reserve]] lies along the left bank of the river opposite the town of [[Pushchino]] and is known for its [[wisent]] breeding nursery. {{cn|date=May 2014}}\n\n== Main tributaries ==\n[[Image:RybnoeDistrict 06-13 Konstantinovo Oka River 01.jpg|thumbnail|right|The Oka River in Ryazan Oblast, near [[Rybnoye, Ryazan Oblast|Rybnoye]]]]\nThe largest tributaries of the Oka are, from source to mouth:<ref name=gvr/>\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Zusha River|Zusha]] (right)\n* [[Upa River|Upa]] (right)\n* [[Zhizdra River|Zhizdra]] (left)\n* [[Ugra River (Oka)|Ugra]] (left)\n* [[Protva River|Protva]] (left)\n* [[Nara River (Russia)|Nara]] (left)\n* [[Lopasnya River|Lopasnya]] (left)\n* [[Besputa River|Besputa]] (right)\n* [[Osyotr River|Osyotr]] (right)\n* [[Moskva River|Moskva]] (left)\n* [[Pronya River (Russia)|Pronya]] (right)\n* [[Para River (Russia)|Para]] (right)\n* [[Pra River (Russia)|Pra]] (left)\n* [[Gus River|Gus]] (left)\n* [[Moksha River|Moksha]] (right)\n* [[Tyosha River|Tyosha]] (right)\n* [[Ushna River|Ushna]] (left)\n* [[Kishma River|Kishma]] (right)\n* [[Klyazma River|Klyazma]] (left)\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Cities and towns on the Oka ==\n{{Location map+|Russia Central Federal District|width=400|float=right|caption=Cities on the Oka\n|places=\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=56.33|long=44.00|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=Nizhny Novgorod|position=top}} <!--wow-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=56.23|long=43.45|mark=Red dot.svg|label=}}<!--Dzerzhinsk-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=56.13|long=43.06|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Gorbatov-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=55.97|long=43.06|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Pavlovo-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=55.55|long=42.20|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Navashino-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=55.56|long=42.02|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=Murom}}<!--Murom-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.93|long=41.40|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=Kasimov}}<!--Kasimov-->\n\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.60|long=39.70|label=Ryazan|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|position=bottom}}\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=55.08|long=38.62|label=Kolomna|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|position=right}}\n\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.83|long=37.62|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Paschino-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.88|long=37.22|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Protvino-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.83|long=38.02|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Kashira-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.88|long=38.00|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Stupino-->\n\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.91|long=37.40|label=Serpukhov |position=top|mark=Red dot.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.73|long=37.18|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Tarusa-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.52|long=37.10|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Aleksin-->\n\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.50|long=36.28|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=Kaluga|position=left}}\n\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.01|long=36.15|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=Belyov}}\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.10|long=36.25|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Chekalin-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=52.97|long=36.04|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=Oryol}}\n\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=55.750 |long=37.6166 |label=MOSCOW |position=top|mark=City locator 16.svg}}\n}}\n* [[Oryol]]\n* [[Belyov]]\n* [[Chekalin]]\n* [[Kaluga]]\n* [[Aleksin]]\n* [[Tarusa]]\n* [[Serpukhov]]\n* [[Stupino, Stupinsky District, Moscow Oblast|Stupino]]\n* [[Kashira]]\n* [[Protvino]]\n* [[Pushchino]]\n* [[Kolomna]]\n* [[Ryazan]]\n* [[Kasimov]]\n* [[Murom]]\n* [[Pavlovo, Pavlovsky District, Nizhny Novgorod Oblast|Pavlovo]]\n* [[Navashino]]\n* [[Gorbatov (town)|Gorbatov]]\n* [[Dzerzhinsk, Russia|Dzerzhinsk]]\n* [[Nizhny Novgorod]]\n\n==In culture==\nThe River appears as the title and main theme in a popular, nostalgia filled song (in which it is compared to the [[Vistula]] river in Poland) of the [[Polish 1st Tadeusz Ko\u015bciuszko Infantry Division]] which was formed nearby in 1943. The unit fought all the way to Berlin alongside the Red Army. It was written by [[Leon Pasternak]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{GEOnet2|32FA878A66E33774E0440003BA962ED3|Oka}}\n* {{commonscat-inline|Oka River}}\n\n{{Volga River}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Rivers of Kaluga Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Moscow Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Nizhny Novgorod Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Oryol Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Ryazan Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Tula Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Vladimir Oblast]]\n", "text_old": "{{ref improve|date=April 2020}}\n{{About|a river in western Russia|the river in Siberia with the same name|Oka River (Siberia)|other uses|Oka (disambiguation){{!}}Oka}}\n{{Infobox river\n| name               = Oka\n| name_native        = \u041e\u043a\u0430\u0301\n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = \n| name_etymology     = \n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = NN Spit from Fedorovskogo Embankment 08-2016 img2.jpg\n| image_size         = 270\n| image_caption      = The Oka riverbank in [[Nizhny Novgorod]]\n| map                = Okarivermap.png\n| map_size           = 270\n| map_caption        = Map of the Volga watershed with the Oka highlighted\n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n<!---------------------- LOCATION -->\n| subdivision_type1  = Country\n| subdivision_name1  = [[Russia]]\n| subdivision_type2  = \n| subdivision_name2  = \n| subdivision_type3  = \n| subdivision_name3  = \n| subdivision_type4  = \n| subdivision_name4  = \n| subdivision_type5  = Cities\n| subdivision_name5  = [[Oryol]], [[Kaluga]], [[Serpukhov]], [[Kolomna]], [[Ryazan]], [[Murom]], [[Dzerzhinsk, Russia|Dzerzhinsk]], [[Nizhny Novgorod]]\n<!---------------------- PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS -->\n| length             = {{convert|1500|km|mi|abbr=on}} \n| width_min          = \n| width_avg          = \n| width_max          = \n| depth_min          = \n| depth_avg          = \n| depth_max          = \n| discharge1_location= \n| discharge1_min     = \n| discharge1_avg     = {{convert|1260|m3/s|cuft/s|abbr=on}}\n| discharge1_max     = \n<!---------------------- BASIN FEATURES -->\n| source1            = \n| source1_location   = [[Oryol Oblast]]\n| source1_coordinates= {{coord|52|21|45|N|36|13|20|E|display=inline}}\n| source1_elevation  = {{convert|226|m|abbr=on}}\n| mouth              = [[Volga River]]\n| mouth_location     = [[Nizhny Novgorod]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = {{coord|56|19|55|N|43|58|53|E|display=inline,title}}\n| mouth_elevation    = {{convert|67|m|abbr=on}}\n| progression        = {{RVolga}}\n| river_system       = \n| basin_size         = {{convert|245000|km2|abbr=on}}\n| tributaries_left   = \n| tributaries_right  = \n| custom_label       = \n| custom_data        = \n| extra              = \n}}\n\n'''Oka''' ({{lang-ru|\u041e\u043a\u0430\u0301}}, {{IPA-ru|\u0250\u02c8ka|IPA}}) is a river in central [[Russia]], the largest right [[tributary]] of the [[Volga]]. It flows through the regions of [[Oryol Oblast|Oryol]], [[Tula Oblast|Tula]], [[Kaluga Oblast|Kaluga]], [[Moscow Oblast|Moscow]], [[Ryazan Oblast|Ryazan]], [[Vladimir Oblast|Vladimir]] and [[Nizhny Novgorod Oblast|Nizhny Novgorod]] and is navigable over a large part of its total length, as far upstream as to the town of [[Kaluga]]. Its length is {{convert|1500|km|abbr=on}} and its catchment area is {{convert|245000|km2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=gvr>[http://textual.ru/gvr/index.php?card=177924 \u00ab\u0420\u0435\u043a\u0430 \u041e\u043a\u0430\u00bb], Russian State Water Registry</ref> The Russian capital [[Moscow]] sits on one of the Oka's tributaries&mdash;the [[Moskva River]].\n\n== Name and history ==\nThe Oka river was the homeland of the Eastern Slavic [[Vyatichi]] tribe.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=ktyM07I9HXwC&pg=PT36&lpg=PT36&dq=eastern+slavs+volga+homeland&source=bl&ots=y7TaAaSKS6&sig=ACfU3U1vtKvEHqbTB67TLcOOQEfoGfbTaQ&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjf4_eU9-TgAhWJDuwKHeOyBfMQ6AEwCXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Ukraine: A History, 4th Edition|last=Subtelny|first=Orest|date=2009-11-10|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=9781442697287|language=en}}</ref> By the 5th century the land around the Oka river was inhabited by different Slavic tribes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mouzenidis.com/russia/article/history-of-russia|title=History of Russia, the Russian Empire, in ancient times, read {{!}} we know everything - Mouzenidis Travel|work=Mouzenidis Travel|access-date=2018-11-18|language=en}}</ref>{{better source|date=April 2020}} The Baltic tribe of [[Galindians]] also lived in the western part of the Oka basin.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tarasov|first=\u0418\u043b\u044c\u044f \u0422\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432 / Ilia|title=\u0411\u0430\u043b\u0442\u044b \u0432 \u043c\u0438\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432. \u0413\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0434\u044b // \u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0442, \u2116 3-4, 2017. \u0421. 95-124.|url=https://www.academia.edu/37147068/%D0%91%D0%B0%D0%BB%D1%82%D1%8B_%D0%B2_%D0%BC%D0%B8%D0%B3%D1%80%D0%B0%D1%86%D0%B8%D1%8F%D1%85_%D0%92%D0%B5%D0%BB%D0%B8%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%B3%D0%BE_%D0%BF%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B5%D1%81%D0%B5%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%8F_%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%B4%D0%BE%D0%B2._%D0%93%D0%B0%D0%BB%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B4%D1%8B_%D0%98%D1%81%D1%82%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%B8%D1%87%D0%B5%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B8%D0%B9_%D1%84%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%BC%D0%B0%D1%82_3-4_2017._%D0%A1._95-124|journal=\u0411\u0430\u043b\u0442\u044b \u0432 \u043c\u0438\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432. \u0413\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0434\u044b|language=en}}</ref> Turkic tribes also inhabited the Oka area. The Oka river was also inhabited by Vikings and other peoples from Scandinavia.{{cn|date=April 2020}} Artifacts of Scandinavian origin were found along the Oka - Volga route.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=yUV-AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT892&lpg=PT892&dq=along+the+volga+waterway+scandinavian+artefacts&source=bl&ots=-PxRctP2Zn&sig=ACfU3U0y8eah4puHeGp5Fi1nmewigfEWIg&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwikysHIodLhAhWQJlAKHWR6AOYQ6AEwAHoECAYQAQ#v=onepage&q=along%20the%20volga%20waterway%20scandinavian%20artefacts&f=false|title=The Viking World|last=Brink|first=Stefan|last2=Price|first2=Neil|date=2008-10-31|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134318254|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Threads of Empire: Loyalty and Tsarist Authority in Bashkiria, 1552-1917|last=Steinwedel|first=Charles|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2016|isbn=|location=|pages=13}}</ref> There is no consensus opinion where the name Oka originated from.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nFrom the Mongol conquest until about 1633, the Oka was the last line of defense against steppe raiders. Later [[Zasechnaya cherta]], a chain of fortification lines, was created to protect [[Grand Duchy of Moscow]] and later the [[Tsardom of Russia]] from the [[Crimean\u2013Nogai slave raids in Eastern Europe|Crimean-Nogai Raids]]. It was south of the original line along the Oka River.\n\nThe river gave its name to the [[Upper Oka Principalities]], situated upstream from [[Tarusa]]. In 1221 Grand Duke [[Yuri II of Vladimir]] founded [[Nizhny Novgorod]], later to become one of largest Russian cities, to protect the Oka's confluence with the Volga. The [[Qasim Khanate]], a Muslim polity, occupied the middle reaches of the Oka (around the city of [[Kasimov]]) in the 15th and 16th centuries.\n\nBefore the construction of the railways in the mid-19th century and the building of the [[Moscow Canal]] in the 1930s, the Oka, along with its tributary [[Moscow River|Moskva]], served as an important transportation route connecting [[Moscow]] with the Volga River. Due to the Oka's and Moskva's meandering courses, travel was not particularly fast: for example, it took [[Cornelis de Bruijn]] around 10 days to sail from Moscow down these two rivers to Nizhny Novgorod in 1703.<ref>{{citation\n|first=Cornelis de |last=Bruin\n|title=Voyage au Levant: c'est-\u00e0-dire, dans les principaux endroits de l'Asie Mineure, dans les isles de Chio, Rhodes, Chypre, etc., de m\u00eame que dans les plus consid\u00e9rables villes d'Egypte, de Syrie, et Terre Sainte.\n|volume=3\n|publisher=J.-B.-C. Bauche le fils|year= 1725\n|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=ctUWAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA250|pages=233\u2013247}}\n</ref> Traveling upstream may have been even slower, as the boats had to be pulled by [[burlaks]].<ref>{{harvnb|Bruin|1725|p=240}}</ref>\n\n== Landmarks ==\nThe banks of the river are dotted with historical and cultural sites, including the medieval monasteries of [[Murom]], the mosques and minarets of [[Kasimov]], the fortified [[Kremlin (fortification)|kremlin]]s of [[Kolomna]] and [[Serpukhov]], the memorial houses of [[Vasily Polenov]] and [[Sergey Yesenin]], the excavated ruins of [[Old Ryazan]] and the [[Shukhov tower on the Oka River|Oka Shukhov Tower]].\n\nThe [[Prioksko-Terrasny Biosphere Reserve]] lies along the left bank of the river opposite the town of [[Pushchino]] and is known for its [[wisent]] breeding nursery. {{cn|date=May 2014}}\n\n== Main tributaries ==\n[[Image:RybnoeDistrict 06-13 Konstantinovo Oka River 01.jpg|thumbnail|right|The Oka River in Ryazan Oblast, near [[Rybnoye, Ryazan Oblast|Rybnoye]]]]\nThe largest tributaries of the Oka are, from source to mouth:<ref name=gvr/>\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Zusha River|Zusha]] (right)\n* [[Upa River|Upa]] (right)\n* [[Zhizdra River|Zhizdra]] (left)\n* [[Ugra River (Oka)|Ugra]] (left)\n* [[Protva River|Protva]] (left)\n* [[Nara River (Russia)|Nara]] (left)\n* [[Lopasnya River|Lopasnya]] (left)\n* [[Besputa River|Besputa]] (right)\n* [[Osyotr River|Osyotr]] (right)\n* [[Moskva River|Moskva]] (left)\n* [[Pronya River (Russia)|Pronya]] (right)\n* [[Para River (Russia)|Para]] (right)\n* [[Pra River (Russia)|Pra]] (left)\n* [[Gus River|Gus]] (left)\n* [[Moksha River|Moksha]] (right)\n* [[Tyosha River|Tyosha]] (right)\n* [[Ushna River|Ushna]] (left)\n* [[Klyazma River|Klyazma]] (left)\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Cities and towns on the Oka ==\n{{Location map+|Russia Central Federal District|width=400|float=right|caption=Cities on the Oka\n|places=\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=56.33|long=44.00|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=Nizhny Novgorod|position=top}} <!--wow-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=56.23|long=43.45|mark=Red dot.svg|label=}}<!--Dzerzhinsk-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=56.13|long=43.06|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Gorbatov-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=55.97|long=43.06|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Pavlovo-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=55.55|long=42.20|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Navashino-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=55.56|long=42.02|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=Murom}}<!--Murom-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.93|long=41.40|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=Kasimov}}<!--Kasimov-->\n\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.60|long=39.70|label=Ryazan|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|position=bottom}}\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=55.08|long=38.62|label=Kolomna|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|position=right}}\n\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.83|long=37.62|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Paschino-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.88|long=37.22|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Protvino-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.83|long=38.02|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Kashira-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.88|long=38.00|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Stupino-->\n\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.91|long=37.40|label=Serpukhov |position=top|mark=Red dot.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.73|long=37.18|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Tarusa-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.52|long=37.10|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Aleksin-->\n\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.50|long=36.28|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=Kaluga|position=left}}\n\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.01|long=36.15|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=Belyov}}\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=54.10|long=36.25|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=}}<!--Chekalin-->\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=52.97|long=36.04|mark=Dot-yellow.svg|label=Oryol}}\n\n{{Location map~|Russia Central Federal District|lat=55.750 |long=37.6166 |label=MOSCOW |position=top|mark=City locator 16.svg}}\n}}\n* [[Oryol]]\n* [[Belyov]]\n* [[Chekalin]]\n* [[Kaluga]]\n* [[Aleksin]]\n* [[Tarusa]]\n* [[Serpukhov]]\n* [[Stupino, Stupinsky District, Moscow Oblast|Stupino]]\n* [[Kashira]]\n* [[Protvino]]\n* [[Pushchino]]\n* [[Kolomna]]\n* [[Ryazan]]\n* [[Kasimov]]\n* [[Murom]]\n* [[Pavlovo, Pavlovsky District, Nizhny Novgorod Oblast|Pavlovo]]\n* [[Navashino]]\n* [[Gorbatov (town)|Gorbatov]]\n* [[Dzerzhinsk, Russia|Dzerzhinsk]]\n* [[Nizhny Novgorod]]\n\n==In culture==\nThe River appears as the title and main theme in a popular, nostalgia filled song (in which it is compared to the [[Vistula]] river in Poland) of the [[Polish 1st Tadeusz Ko\u015bciuszko Infantry Division]] which was formed nearby in 1943. The unit fought all the way to Berlin alongside the Red Army. It was written by [[Leon Pasternak]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{GEOnet2|32FA878A66E33774E0440003BA962ED3|Oka}}\n* {{commonscat-inline|Oka River}}\n\n{{Volga River}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Rivers of Kaluga Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Moscow Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Nizhny Novgorod Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Oryol Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Ryazan Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Tula Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Vladimir Oblast]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMain tributaries", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oka_River"}
{"title_page": "Andile Lungisa", "text_new": "{{short description|South African politician}}\n'''Andile Lungisa''' (born 21 December 1979 in [[Tsomo]], [[Chris Hani District Municipality]] in the [[Eastern Cape]]) is a [[South Africa]]n politician and the former deputy president of the [[African National Congress Youth League]] (ANCYL). Lungisa is also the former chairperson of the National Youth Development Agency (NYDA) of South Africa as well as the former President of the [[ Panafrican Youth Union| Pan-African Youth Union]] (PYU) and is currently serving as councillor of the ANC at the [[Nelson Mandela Bay Metropolitan Municipality]] in Port Elizabeth.<ref>[https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/2009-06-11-lungisa-is-a-man-of-talents/ Lungisa is a man of talents], [Sowetan Live, 11 June 2009. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref><ref>[https://www.politicsweb.co.za/news-and-analysis/lungisa-elected-president-of-pan-african-youth-uni Lungisa elected president of Pan-African Youth Union - ANCYL], Politics Web, 8 December 2011. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref><ref>[https://m.polity.org.za/article/nelson-mandela-bay-anc-still-battling-factionalism-2016-09-09 Nelson Mandela Bay ANC still battling factionalism], 9 September 2016. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early political career===\n\nLungisa became active in politics from the age of 14 through the [[South African Students Congress]] (SASCO) in the early 1990s. He was later elected chairperson of SASCO in the region, which includes [[Port Elizabeth]] and [[Grahamstown]]. In 1998, Lungisa started an [[African National Congress Youth League|ANCYL]] branch in the western suburbs of [[Port Elizabeth]] called 'City Central', and became its executive committee member. In 2001, he was elected deputy regional chairperson of the Nelson Mandela Bay ANC region.\n\n===2008 - present=== \n\nLungisa was elected as the deputy president of the ANC Youth League in April 2008.  He was elected to deputise [[Julius Malema]] who got elected president at the conference held in [[Mangaung]]. Vuyiswa Tulelo was elected national secretary-general, Steve Ngubeni the deputy secretary-general and [[Pule Mabe]] as treasurer-general.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/ANCYL-elects-top-five-20080407 ANCYL elects top five], [[News24]], 7 April 2008. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Lungisa was supported by the ANCYL to go serve as the chairperson of the newly established National Youth Development Agency (NYDA) when nominations for candidates opened in March 2009<ref>[http://www.fin24.com/Economy/New-youth-agency-has-rocky-start-20090301 New youth agency has rocky start], Fin24, 1 March 2009. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>, a position he held from April 2009 until April 2013 when Yershen Pillay took over.<ref>[https://www.vukuzenzele.gov.za/fresh-faces-nyda-board fresh faces for NYDA board], Vukuzenzele, May 2013 Issue. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>\n\nLungisa was elected President of the [[Panafrican Youth Union|Pan-African Youth Union]] (PYU) in a conference that took place from 2 to 5 December 2011 in [[Khartoum]], [[Sudan]]. He had been Vice President of the structure for a three-year term.<ref>[https://www.gov.za/ministry-congratulates-andile-lungisa Ministry congratulates Andile Lungisa], Government of South Africa, 7 December 2011. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>\n\nHe currently serves as councillor for the [[Nelson Mandela Metropolitan Municipality]],  appointed the Member of the Mayoral Committee responsible for the municipal Department of Infrastructure and Engineering.<ref>[https://m.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Local/UD-News/state-of-disaster-water-crisis-looming-20200414 State of disaster: Water crisis looming], [[News24]], 14 April 2020</ref>. \n\nHe was elected in 2017 as regional chairperson of the ANC in the Nelson Mandela region<ref>[https://www.politicsweb.co.za/news-and-analysis/andile-lungisa-elected-to-lead-anc-in-nmb Andile Lungisa elected to lead ANC in NMB], Politics Web, 12 March 2017. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref> but resigned shortly afterwards when the national executive committee (NEC) found that he broke the Constitution for contesting on a regional level while serving as provincial executive committee (PEC) member.<ref>[Andile Lungisa steps down as ANC regional chair - https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/politics/2017-03-27-lungisa-steps-down-as-anc-regional-chairpersonnec-backs-mantashe/ Lungisa steps down as chairperson, NEC backs Mantashe], Business Live, 27 March 2017. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref> <ref>[https://www.enca.com/south-africa/mantashe-adamant-that-lungisa-should-resign Mantashe adamant that Lungisa should resign], eNCA, 18 March 2017. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\nIn April 2018, Lungisa was found guilty of assault with the intent to cause grievous bodily harm for hitting [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|DA]] councillor Rano Kayser over the head with a glass water jug intentionally and without provocation during a heated council meeting in October 2016. The incident was caught on camera and Lungisa was sentenced to 2 years which he is appealing. He said he acted in self-defense but Judge Morne Cannon of the Port Elizabeth Magistrates Court, said Lungisa changed his versions throughout the trial and his evidence could not be trusted.<ref>[https://m.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/anc-ecape-heavyweight-andile-lungisa-found-guilty-of-assault-20180417 ANC Eastern Cape heavyweight found guilty of assault], [[News24]], 17 April 2018. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref><ref>[https://www.heraldlive.co.za/news/2018-04-17-andile-lungisa-found-guilty/ Andile Lungisa found guilty], Herald Live, 17 April 2018. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref><ref>[https://www.dailysun.co.za/News/National/ancs-andile-lungisa-gets-2-years-in-jail-20180509 ANC's Andile Lungisa gets 2 years in jail], Daily Sun, 9 May 2018. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, Lungisa and three others appeared before the '''Johannesburg Specialised Commercial Crime Court''' over allegations of fraud and money-laundeering relating to a R2.5 million paid by the Department of Arts and Culture for the 'Nelson Mandela Sports Day concert'<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/Former-NYDA-head-Andile-Lungisa-arrested-20131004 Former NYDA head Andile Lungisa arrested], [[News24]], 4 October 2013. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>. They allegedly promised that [[USA|US]] singer [[R Kelly]] would perform at the concert, but he did not. Later it was discovered that R Kelly's management had been unaware of the event.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2013-10-04-former-nyda-boss-andile-lungisa-arrested-for-fraud/ Former NYDA boss Andile Lungisa arrested for fraud], Timeslive, 4 October 2013. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>. Their case was withdrawn in October 2016.<ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1307449/lungisa-returns-to-anc-job-as-fraud-case-is-withdrawn/ Lungisa returns to ANC job as fraud case is withdrawn], [[The Citizen (South Africa)|The Citizen]], 7 October 2016. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Lungisa was asked to resign as Nelson Mandela ANC region chairperson having been in the position for less than a week. In terms of ANC [[Constitution]], Lungisa was supposed to resign first as Eastern Cape ANC provincial executive committee (PEC) member before contesting on a lower level.<ref>[http://risefm.co.za/lungisa-resigns-anc-regional-chair-post-after-nec-cracks-whip/ Lungisa resigns ANC regional chair post after NEC cracks whip], Rise Fm, Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref><ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1456273/pic-gwede-mantashes-angry-letter-lungisa/ READ: Gwede Mantashe's angry letter to Zuma's anointed one], [[The Citizen (South Africa)|The Citizen]], 14 March 2017. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lungisa, Andile}}\n[[Category:Members of the African National Congress]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n{{SouthAfrica-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African politician}}\n'''Andile Lungisa''' (born 21 December 1979 in [[Tsomo]], [[Chris Hani District Municipality]] in the [[Eastern Cape]]) is a [[South Africa]]n politician and the former deputy president of the [[African National Congress Youth League]] (ANCYL). Lungisa is also the former chairperson of the National Youth Development Agency (NYDA) of South Africa as well as the former President of the [[ Panafrican Youth Union| Pan-African Youth Union]] (PYU) and is currently serving as councillor of the ANC at the [[Nelson Mandela Bay Metropolitan Municipality]] in Port Elizabeth<ref>[https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/2009-06-11-lungisa-is-a-man-of-talents/ Lungisa is a man of talents], [Sowetan Live, 11 June 2009. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref> <ref>[https://www.politicsweb.co.za/news-and-analysis/lungisa-elected-president-of-pan-african-youth-uni Lungisa elected president of Pan-African Youth Union - ANCYL], Politics Web, 8 December 2011. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref> <ref>[https://m.polity.org.za/article/nelson-mandela-bay-anc-still-battling-factionalism-2016-09-09 Nelson Mandela Bay ANC still battling factionalism], 9 September 2016. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early political career===\n\nLungisa became active in politics from the age of 14 through the [[South African Students Congress]] (SASCO) in the early 1990s. He was later elected chairperson of SASCO in the region, which includes [[Port Elizabeth]] and [[Grahamstown]]. In 1998, Lungisa started an [[African National Congress Youth League|ANCYL]] branch in the western suburbs of [[Port Elizabeth]] called 'City Central', and became its executive committee member. In 2001, he was elected deputy regional chairperson of the Nelson Mandela Bay ANC region.\n\n===2008 - present=== \n\nLungisa was elected as the deputy president of the ANC Youth League in April 2008.  He was elected to deputise [[Julius Malema]] who got elected president at the conference held in [[Mangaung]]. Vuyiswa Tulelo was elected national secretary-general, Steve Ngubeni the deputy secretary-general and [[Pule Mabe]] as treasurer-general<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/ANCYL-elects-top-five-20080407 ANCYL elects top five], [[News24]], 7 April 2008. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Lungisa was supported by the ANCYL to go serve as the chairperson of the newly established National Youth Development Agency (NYDA) when nominations for candidates opened in March 2009<ref>[http://www.fin24.com/Economy/New-youth-agency-has-rocky-start-20090301 New youth agency has rocky start], Fin24, 1 March 2009. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>, a position he held from April 2009 until April 2013 when Yershen Pillay took over<ref>[https://www.vukuzenzele.gov.za/fresh-faces-nyda-board fresh faces for NYDA board], Vukuzenzele, May 2013 Issue. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>\n\nLungisa was elected President of the [[Panafrican Youth Union|Pan-African Youth Union]] (PYU) in a conference that took place from 2 to 5 December 2011 in [[Khartoum]], [[Sudan]]. He had been Vice President of the structure for a three-year term<ref>[https://www.gov.za/ministry-congratulates-andile-lungisa Ministry congratulates Andile Lungisa], Government of South Africa, 7 December 2011. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>\n\nHe currently serves as councillor for the [[Nelson Mandela Metropolitan Municipality]],  appointed the Member of the Mayoral Committee responsible for the municipal Department of Infrastructure and Engineering<ref>[https://m.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Local/UD-News/state-of-disaster-water-crisis-looming-20200414 State of disaster: Water crisis looming], [[News24]], 14 April 2020</ref>. \n\nHe was elected in 2017 as regional chairperson of the ANC in the Nelson Mandela region<ref>[https://www.politicsweb.co.za/news-and-analysis/andile-lungisa-elected-to-lead-anc-in-nmb Andile Lungisa elected to lead ANC in NMB], Politics Web, 12 March 2017. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref> but resigned shortly afterwards when the national executive committee (NEC) found that he broke the Constitution for contesting on a regional level while serving as provincial executive committee (PEC) member<ref>[Andile Lungisa steps down as ANC regional chair - https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/politics/2017-03-27-lungisa-steps-down-as-anc-regional-chairpersonnec-backs-mantashe/ Lungisa steps down as chairperson, NEC backs Mantashe], Business Live, 27 March 2017. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref> <ref>[https://www.enca.com/south-africa/mantashe-adamant-that-lungisa-should-resign Mantashe adamant that Lungisa should resign], eNCA, 18 March 2017. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\nIn April 2018, Lungisa was found guilty of assault with the intent to cause grievous bodily harm for hitting [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|DA]] councillor Rano Kayser over the head with a glass water jug intentionally and without provocation during a heated council meeting in October 2016. The incident was caught on camera and Lungisa was sentenced to 2 years which he is appealing. He said he acted in self-defense but Judge Morne Cannon of the Port Elizabeth Magistrates Court, said Lungisa changed his versions throughout the trial and his evidence could not be trusted<ref>[https://m.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/anc-ecape-heavyweight-andile-lungisa-found-guilty-of-assault-20180417 ANC Eastern Cape heavyweight found guilty of assault], [[News24]], 17 April 2018. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref> <ref>[https://www.heraldlive.co.za/news/2018-04-17-andile-lungisa-found-guilty/ Andile Lungisa found guilty], Herald Live, 17 April 2018. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref> <ref>[https://www.dailysun.co.za/News/National/ancs-andile-lungisa-gets-2-years-in-jail-20180509 ANC's Andile Lungisa gets 2 years in jail], Daily Sun, 9 May 2018. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, Lungisa and three others appeared before the '''Johannesburg Specialised Commercial Crime Court''' over allegations of fraud and money-laundeering relating to a R2.5 million paid by the Department of Arts and Culture for the 'Nelson Mandela Sports Day concert'<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/Former-NYDA-head-Andile-Lungisa-arrested-20131004 Former NYDA head Andile Lungisa arrested], [[News24]], 4 October 2013. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>. They allegedly promised that [[USA|US]] singer [[R Kelly]] would perform at the concert, but he did not. Later it was discovered that R Kelly's management had been unaware of the event<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2013-10-04-former-nyda-boss-andile-lungisa-arrested-for-fraud/ Former NYDA boss Andile Lungisa arrested for fraud], Timeslive, 4 October 2013. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>. Their case was withdrawn in October 2016<ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1307449/lungisa-returns-to-anc-job-as-fraud-case-is-withdrawn/ Lungisa returns to ANC job as fraud case is withdrawn], [[The Citizen (South Africa)|The Citizen]], 7 October 2016. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>.\n\nIn March 2017, Lungisa was asked to resign as Nelson Mandela ANC region chairperson having been in the position for less than a week. In terms of ANC [[Constitution]], Lungisa was supposed to resign first as Eastern Cape ANC provincial executive committee (PEC) member before contesting on a lower level<ref>[http://risefm.co.za/lungisa-resigns-anc-regional-chair-post-after-nec-cracks-whip/ Lungisa resigns ANC regional chair post after NEC cracks whip], Rise Fm, Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref> <ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1456273/pic-gwede-mantashes-angry-letter-lungisa/ READ: Gwede Mantashe's angry letter to Zuma's anointed one], [[The Citizen (South Africa)|The Citizen]], 14 March 2017. Retrieved 21 April 2020</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lungisa, Andile}}\n[[Cate